"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452273","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>Under Article 6 of the Reception Conditions Directive 2013/13, EU member states are required to ensure that asylum applicants seeking international protection within their territory are provided with a document showing their status as an applicant or testifying that person is allowed to stay in the member state whilst the application is pending or being examined.</p><p>The process for issuing such a document will vary from country to country.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-23T16:51:14.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452273/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452273/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Asylum: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what information they have about whether government documents are being issued by EU member states to those seeking asylum in countries in the Schengen area while they await a decision on their application for asylum.","false","Biography information for Lord Higgins",,"Lord Higgins","HL6174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452274","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>Under Article 25 of the Qualification Directive asylum seekers accepted as refugees in an EU member state will be issued a refugee status travel document, in the form set out in the Schedule to the Geneva Convention, for the purpose of travel outside their territory unless there are compelling reasons of national security or public order which prevent this.</p><p>It is normal practice for member states to distribute specimen documents between states. All specimen documents are stored securely in the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-22T15:09:37.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452274/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452274/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Asylum: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether EU member states within the Schengen area are issuing a standard form of passport or other document to those they accept as asylum seekers or whether individual countries decide on the format to use; whether they have examined any sample of such document; and if so, whether they will place in the Library of the House any examples they may have.","false","Biography information for Lord Higgins",,"Lord Higgins","HL6175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452275","Home Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government is committed to tackling domestic violence and abuse. Broken Rainbow plays an important role in supporting lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender victims of domestic abuse, and the Home Office has informed Broken Rainbow that it will be renewing funding to support its helpline for 2016/17.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-24T16:43:18.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452275/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452275/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Broken Rainbow UK","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to support the Manchester-based charity Broken Rainbow.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hussein-Ece",,"Baroness Hussein-Ece","HL6176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452276","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Government is committed to growing the social investment market, as shown through initiatives like Big Society Capital and the Social Investment Tax Relief. Cabinet Office recognises that “profit with purpose” businesses are a growing and important part of the social economy. Cabinet Office is engaging with stakeholders to better identify, support and promote this sector.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-02-25T17:45:07.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452276/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452276/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-11","Business","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps the Cabinet Office intends to take to increase the number of profit-with-purpose businesses in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL6177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452277","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-23","<p>Non-profit institutions accounted for 3.1 per cent of real GDP in 2014, with the output of this sector increasing 0.9 per cent over the same period. ONS data do not produce statistics for ‘profit-with-purpose’ companies.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-02-23T17:31:52.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452277/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452277/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-11","Business","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the potential contribution of profit-with-purpose companies to UK gross value added.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL6178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452278","Department for Education","false","2016-02-24","<p>As the Prime Minister made clear in his speech on 11 January 2016, the government understands the importance of those first crucial years of life and that we need to get parenting and the early years right if we are to improve children’s life chances. The government will be publishing a Life Chances strategy in the spring which will set out a comprehensive plan to fight disadvantage and extend opportunity, including policies to give children the best start in life.</p><p>The government is already implementing a range of policies which recognise the contribution of the first 1001 days of a child’s life to its subsequent academic and other attainment, which are detailed below.</p><p> </p><p>Healthy Child Programme</p><p>The evidence based Healthy Child Programme is the universal service offered to every family. Delivered by health visitors, the programme centres on a series of screening tests, immunisations, developmental reviews, and information and guidance to support families of children aged 0-5 years. Since October 2015 there have been five mandated child development reviews, to provide a national standard format to ensure universal coverage and ongoing improvements in public health. Effective implementation of the Healthy Child Programme should lead to readiness for school and improved learning.</p><p> </p><p>Best Start in Life programme</p><p>One of Public Health England’s (PHE) national priorities is to ensure that every child has the best start in life, so that they are ready to learn at age two and ready for school at five. The Best Start in Life programme provides national leadership to support local areas to take a whole system approach to commission and provide evidence based services and interventions which improve child health outcomes and reduce inequalities. PHE also has has also published a range of professional guidance for best practice to support families in the first 1001 days.</p><p> </p><p>Integrated Review (IR)</p><p>In 2013, DfE ran a joint Integrated Review pilot with the Department of Health (DH) which focused on two-year-olds in registered childcare settings. This was to test out the most effective way of undertaking the early years progress check with the universal DH Healthy Child Programme and providing parents with a holistic review of their child’s development. In 2015, we provided funding to support the roll out of the IR by all local authorities in England. We are currently piloting the second phase of the IR with eight local authority pilot areas to test different local models of how early years practitioners can collaborate with health professionals to identify parents of two year-olds not in registered childcare settings, so that their children can also benefit from an Integrated Review.</p><p> </p><p>Early Learning for Two Year Olds</p><p>There is a strong body of evidence that shows good quality childcare and pre-school provision, especially from age two and upwards, has positive benefits on children’s all round attainment and behaviour. For this reason the government introduced the early learning for two-year-olds programme in September 2013 for 130,000 of the most disadvantaged children in England. In September 2014, the programme was later expanded to 260,000 of the most disadvantaged children in England. The programme is becoming increasingly popular amongst eligible parents.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-24T17:19:08.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452278/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452278/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Pre-school Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what policies they intend to implement in recognition of the contribution of the first 1,000 days of a child’s life to its subsequent academic and other attainment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL6179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452279","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>In both 2014/15 and 2009/10, primary schools reported spending around 2 hours per week on Physical Education.</p><p>In 2009/10, secondary school pupils spent on average around 1 hour and 45 minutes in PE each week. No equivalent figures are available for secondary school pupils for 2014/15.</p><p>Through the primary PE and sport premium, primary schools have received over £450m of ring-fenced funding to improve PE and sport. We have committed to continue this funding until 2020. In December 2015, we published a research report looking at how schools used the primary PE and sport premium and the impact of the fund on PE and sports provision. The findings show that 87% of schools reported that the quality of PE teaching had increased since the introduction of the premium. 84% of schools reported an increase in pupil engagement in PE during curricular time and in the levels of participation in extra-curricular activities. Meanwhile, 70% of schools reported that participation in inter-school competitions had increased and over half of schools reported an increase in intra-school competitions.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-25T15:47:35.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452279/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452279/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Schools: Sports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many hours per week (1) primary, and (2) secondary, school pupils spent participating in sport in 2015 compared to 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL6180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452280","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-02-25","<p>The House of Lords agreed to cease using vellum for public Acts in 1999, with a resolution to that effect being passed on 14 October 1999. That resolution still stands. At that time, the change was not agreed by the House of Commons.</p><p>In the past six years (2009/10 to 2014/15) the Lords has spent a total of £620,440 on vellum Acts; an average of just over £103,000 per year.</p><p>This is despite the availability of archival paper which is of extremely high quality and durability.</p><p>Private Acts of Parliament have been printed on archival quality paper since 1956, and I am not aware that vellum is now used for any other UK governmental or parliamentary records.</p><p>The National Archives has confirmed the view it took in 1999: that it does not require a vellum copy, and that archival quality paper is sufficient to maintain the public record. It also maintains a comprehensive database of legislation, both “as originally enacted” and “as amended”, on <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.legislation.gov.uk</a>.</p><p>Switching from vellum to high quality archival paper would, on a conservative estimate, save approximately 80% on current costs - or around £80,000 per year. The exact level of savings to public funds will depend on the number of Acts passed, and number of pages per Act, per year, and the precise specification and contractual arrangements agreed for future printing.</p><p>As well as being an expensive raw material, vellum requires a highly specialised form of printing which is not widely available, the machinery for which is expensive to maintain, and which is likely to be more difficult to procure on the expiry of the House’s current printing contract in March 2016.</p><p>As the start of a new Parliament seemed a natural point at which to implement the change previously agreed by this House, and we were coming to the end of present contracts, the House Committee was content that we were seeking to take forward the House’s 1999 decision. I then wrote to the Chairman of the House of Commons Administration Committee to invite that House to agree to the change. The view of the House of Commons authorities is that this is a matter for the House of Lords.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-02-25T17:44:37.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452280/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452280/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-02-11","Acts: Publishing","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees why the use of vellum for the record copies of Acts of Parliament has been abandoned without the passage through both Houses of a resolution to authorise its discontinuation.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL6181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452281","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>Information on the total volume of milk supplied to schools in 1986 and 2015 is not held centrally.</p><p>The School Food Standards require that milk is made available to all pupils. Where milk is served as part of lunch, it is provided free to all pupils in reception, year 1 and year 2 and to pupils of all ages who are eligible for free school meals.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-25T16:09:21.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452281/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452281/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","School Milk","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the total volume of milk supplied to schools in (1) 1986, and (2) 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL6182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452282","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The decision not to pursue the transfer of custody healthcare commissioning from Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) to NHS England was taken in the context of wider decisions about the Provisional Police Funding Settlement for 2016/17, details of which were announced to Parliament in a written statement by the Minister of State for Policing, Crime and Criminal Justice and Victims on 17 December.</p><p>The Government is clear that Police and Crime Commissioners should retain full flexibility to be able to prioritise resources towards police custody healthcare functions based on their local needs.</p><p>A number of sources of information and guidance are available to PCCs to inform their commissioning of custody healthcare services.</p><p>The Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1983 (PACE) sets out the statutory framework for custodial care and the rights and entitlements of a detainee in police custody. The College of Policing, as the professional body for policing, has published Approved Professional Practice (APP) on custody and detention. Police officers and staff are expected to have regard to the APP in discharging their responsibilities.The APP references wider guidance published by professional medical bodies including the Faculty of Forensic and Legal Medicine. In addition there is a NHS England national service specification setting out clinical standards for the commissioning and provision of police custody healthcare functions. This is currently being reviewed and updated.</p><p>In many police force areas the close ties which PCCs have established to local NHS England commissioners over recent years have already helped to drive up the standards and quality of provision. On 11 February my Rt Hon Friend the Home Secretary and my Right Honourable Friend the Secretary of State for Health wrote to Police and Crime Commissioners and NHS England Commissioners encouraging them to continue to build upon this work to further improve healthcare service delivery.</p><p>Any recommendations made by the forthcoming independent review of deaths and serious incidents in police custody will be carefully considered in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6184 ; HL6186 ; HL6187","2016-02-23T16:44:22.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452282/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452282/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police Custody: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they decided to cancel the transfer of police custody healthcare services to the NHS after several years of preparation; whether that change in policy was announced to Parliament; and what assessment they have made of how that decision will ensure equivalent standards and quality of healthcare and safety of patients in all police services across England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL6183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452283","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The decision not to pursue the transfer of custody healthcare commissioning from Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) to NHS England was taken in the context of wider decisions about the Provisional Police Funding Settlement for 2016/17, details of which were announced to Parliament in a written statement by the Minister of State for Policing, Crime and Criminal Justice and Victims on 17 December.</p><p>The Government is clear that Police and Crime Commissioners should retain full flexibility to be able to prioritise resources towards police custody healthcare functions based on their local needs.</p><p>A number of sources of information and guidance are available to PCCs to inform their commissioning of custody healthcare services.</p><p>The Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1983 (PACE) sets out the statutory framework for custodial care and the rights and entitlements of a detainee in police custody. The College of Policing, as the professional body for policing, has published Approved Professional Practice (APP) on custody and detention. Police officers and staff are expected to have regard to the APP in discharging their responsibilities.The APP references wider guidance published by professional medical bodies including the Faculty of Forensic and Legal Medicine. In addition there is a NHS England national service specification setting out clinical standards for the commissioning and provision of police custody healthcare functions. This is currently being reviewed and updated.</p><p>In many police force areas the close ties which PCCs have established to local NHS England commissioners over recent years have already helped to drive up the standards and quality of provision. On 11 February my Rt Hon Friend the Home Secretary and my Right Honourable Friend the Secretary of State for Health wrote to Police and Crime Commissioners and NHS England Commissioners encouraging them to continue to build upon this work to further improve healthcare service delivery.</p><p>Any recommendations made by the forthcoming independent review of deaths and serious incidents in police custody will be carefully considered in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6183 ; HL6186 ; HL6187","2016-02-23T16:44:22.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452283/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452283/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police Custody: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the decision to cancel the transfer of police custody healthcare services to the NHS, what assessment they have made of the minimum standards of training, skills and competence for healthcare professionals working in a police custody setting; and what steps they have taken to advise Police and Crime Commissioners about the need to adhere to such minimum standards for all healthcare professionals, as recommended by the Faculty of Forensic and Legal Medicine, the UK Association of Forensic Nurses, and the College of Paramedics.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL6184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452284","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) document <em>The scope of registration</em> (CQC, 2015) includes a section about those health and care services that lie outside its duties to regulate, and for which providers are not required to register. Within this section, the document classes forensic medical services as a “third party exemption”, because these services are commissioned and paid for directly by police bodies, which are considered to be the “customer” of these services. This differs from healthcare services commissioned and funded by the National Health Service, in which services are arranged and organised for the benefit of patients. A copy of <em>The scope of registration </em>is attached<em>.</em></p><p> </p><p>Nevertheless, the CQC regularly takes part in joint inspections of police healthcare services, in partnership with Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary and Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Probation. The Department, with the CQC and others, is currently considering whether to amend Schedule 2 to the Health and Social Care Act 2008 (Regulated Activities) Regulations 2014 in order to remove the current exemption, and strengthen the CQC’s contribution to these joint inspection arrangements.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-25T12:15:50.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452284/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452284/answer","Scope of registration.pdf","Scope of registration.pdf","The scope of registration","The scope of registration","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452284/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-11","Forensic Science","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why forensic medical services are an exception under Schedule 2 to the Health and Social Care Act 2008 (Regulated Activities) Regulations 2014; why such healthcare services are considered equivalent to other healthcare settings and whether they are subject to the same level of scrutiny; and whether they plan to amend those Regulations to allow the Care Quality Commission powers of inspection of healthcare facilities in police custody.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL6185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452285","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The decision not to pursue the transfer of custody healthcare commissioning from Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) to NHS England was taken in the context of wider decisions about the Provisional Police Funding Settlement for 2016/17, details of which were announced to Parliament in a written statement by the Minister of State for Policing, Crime and Criminal Justice and Victims on 17 December.</p><p>The Government is clear that Police and Crime Commissioners should retain full flexibility to be able to prioritise resources towards police custody healthcare functions based on their local needs.</p><p>A number of sources of information and guidance are available to PCCs to inform their commissioning of custody healthcare services.</p><p>The Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1983 (PACE) sets out the statutory framework for custodial care and the rights and entitlements of a detainee in police custody. The College of Policing, as the professional body for policing, has published Approved Professional Practice (APP) on custody and detention. Police officers and staff are expected to have regard to the APP in discharging their responsibilities.The APP references wider guidance published by professional medical bodies including the Faculty of Forensic and Legal Medicine. In addition there is a NHS England national service specification setting out clinical standards for the commissioning and provision of police custody healthcare functions. This is currently being reviewed and updated.</p><p>In many police force areas the close ties which PCCs have established to local NHS England commissioners over recent years have already helped to drive up the standards and quality of provision. On 11 February my Rt Hon Friend the Home Secretary and my Right Honourable Friend the Secretary of State for Health wrote to Police and Crime Commissioners and NHS England Commissioners encouraging them to continue to build upon this work to further improve healthcare service delivery.</p><p>Any recommendations made by the forthcoming independent review of deaths and serious incidents in police custody will be carefully considered in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6183 ; HL6184 ; HL6187","2016-02-23T16:44:22.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452285/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452285/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police Custody: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the decision to cancel the transfer of police custody healthcare services to the NHS, whether they will put into place, and ensure the appropriate funding for, any recommendations made about minimum standards and quality of such police custody healthcare services for vulnerable detainees as a result of the forthcoming independent review of deaths and serious incidents in police custody.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL6186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452286","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The decision not to pursue the transfer of custody healthcare commissioning from Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) to NHS England was taken in the context of wider decisions about the Provisional Police Funding Settlement for 2016/17, details of which were announced to Parliament in a written statement by the Minister of State for Policing, Crime and Criminal Justice and Victims on 17 December.</p><p>The Government is clear that Police and Crime Commissioners should retain full flexibility to be able to prioritise resources towards police custody healthcare functions based on their local needs.</p><p>A number of sources of information and guidance are available to PCCs to inform their commissioning of custody healthcare services.</p><p>The Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1983 (PACE) sets out the statutory framework for custodial care and the rights and entitlements of a detainee in police custody. The College of Policing, as the professional body for policing, has published Approved Professional Practice (APP) on custody and detention. Police officers and staff are expected to have regard to the APP in discharging their responsibilities.The APP references wider guidance published by professional medical bodies including the Faculty of Forensic and Legal Medicine. In addition there is a NHS England national service specification setting out clinical standards for the commissioning and provision of police custody healthcare functions. This is currently being reviewed and updated.</p><p>In many police force areas the close ties which PCCs have established to local NHS England commissioners over recent years have already helped to drive up the standards and quality of provision. On 11 February my Rt Hon Friend the Home Secretary and my Right Honourable Friend the Secretary of State for Health wrote to Police and Crime Commissioners and NHS England Commissioners encouraging them to continue to build upon this work to further improve healthcare service delivery.</p><p>Any recommendations made by the forthcoming independent review of deaths and serious incidents in police custody will be carefully considered in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6183 ; HL6184 ; HL6186","2016-02-23T16:44:22.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452286/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452286/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police Custody: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 18 January (HL4835), for what reasons the Home Secretary, Theresa May, has decided that the reallocation of custody healthcare "would not be appropriate at this time".","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL6187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452287","Home Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that children and young people are protected and treated appropriately in all circumstances while in police custody. As set out in the Police and Criminal Evidence Act (PACE) 1984 Codes of Practice C&amp;H, every child or young person taken into police custody on suspicion of committing an offence must be provided with an Appropriate Adult, whose role it is to safeguard their rights and welfare. In addition, a parent or legal guardian must be informed of their detention.</p><p>It is the responsibility of the chief officer of each force to adhere to the safeguards set out in PACE and its Codes of Practice. Police forces should ensure that officers interviewing child victims, including victims of sexual assault, are trained to apply the relevant College of Policing and Ministry of Justice guidance. The College of Policing’s Advanced Professional Practice on ‘Concern for a Child’ is clear that the police should always consider the services of a registered intermediary when a vulnerable child victim is interviewed.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-24T16:44:34.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452287/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452287/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police Custody: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child and the policy of the police to support complainants of child sexual assault who are under 18 years of age with specially trained officers, what assessment they have made of the case for extending the use of specially trained officers to support all children and young people under 18 years of age who are brought into police custody, and what plans, if any, they have to make such a change.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL6188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452288","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>The UK has four objectives for the Summit. Most importantly we want to see a renewed commitment to the protection of civilians in conflict, but also smarter financing, a new approach to building resilience to natural hazards before they take place, and a stronger focus on protecting and empowering women and girls.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-02-25T16:49:07.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452288/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452288/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","World Humanitarian Summit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are their priorities for the World Humanitarian Summit in May.","false","Biography information for Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale",,"Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale","HL6189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452289","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>Decisions on who will be in the delegation will be taken nearer the time.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-02-25T16:49:27.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452289/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452289/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","World Humanitarian Summit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who will represent them Government at the World Humanitarian Summit in May.","false","Biography information for Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale",,"Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale","HL6190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452290","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-18","<p>World Health Organisation (WHO) data show that the leading causes of death from infectious diseases amongst adolescent girls and women in Africa are HIV/AIDS, diarrhoeal diseases, respiratory infections, meningitis and malaria. HIV/AIDS is not only the leading cause of death itself, but is also responsible for deaths from many other infectious diseases. The UK is the second largest funder of HIV prevention, care and treatment, and has pledged up to £1 billion for the 2014-16 replenishment of the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB and Malaria. Half of Global Fund resources are used to tackle HIV and almost 60% are invested in programmes that reach women and children.</p><p>The UK puts the empowerment of girls and women at the heart of everything we do. Through our multilateral and bilateral investments we are tackling the barriers that limit their access to services, strengthening health systems, and tackling the stigma and gender-based violence and inequality they face.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-02-18T16:58:20.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452290/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452290/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Africa: Infectious Diseases","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of which infectious diseases are among the leading causes of death for girls and women aged 10 to 19 in Africa, and what steps they are taking, working with individual countries bilaterally, to tackle those diseases.","false","Biography information for Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale",,"Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale","HL6191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452291","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>I have placed in the House Library a copy of the exchange of correspondence from February 1984 between the Secretary of State for Employment and the General Secretary of the TUC.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-22T12:18:37.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452291/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452291/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Trade Unions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will place in the Library of the House a copy of the 1984 agreement on trade union political funding between Lord King of Bridgwater and Lord Murray of Epping Forest, then General Secretary of the TUC.","false","Biography information for Lord Monks",,"Lord Monks","HL6192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452292","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-02-23","<p>Partners and spouses are not entitled to receive meals without charge.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-02-23T17:46:17.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452292/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452292/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-02-11","House of Lords: Catering","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees, further to his Written Answer on 10 February (HL5554), whether partners and spouses of Catering and Retail Services staff are also entitled to receive meals without charge.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL6193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452293","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-23","<p>This is not viewed as a risk by the Government. Localism does not mean that national law can be contravened, nor does it allow the creation of local court systems. Legislation remains the responsibility of Parliament, not local authorities.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-02-23T15:45:39.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452293/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452293/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-11","Local Government: Devolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to the risk that their policy of further localism might lead to local authorities with high Muslim populations adopting Sharia law, if current trends in birth rate continue.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL6194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452294","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>The November 2014 answer (HL 5012) incorrectly referred to question number 211618 as having been responded to by Priti Patel, when in fact the answer was provided by Esther McVey.</p><p> </p><p>I would like to apologise again for this, but would like to be clear that the mistake was to incorrectly state the name of the Minister providing the original response (211618)) and did not relate to the question number. Both responses HL 5012 and 5883 correctly referred the Honourable Lord to question number 211618.</p><p> </p><p>The original reference to question 211618 was provided because the information has not changed; information on benefit receipt by nationality is not available.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-02-25T17:35:57.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452294/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452294/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Social Security Benefits: EU Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Freud on 10 February (HL5883), why the incorrect reference to the 20 November 2014 answer has been repeated, and whether they will now state what is the annual cost of paying in-work benefits to non-UK citizens from other EU countries in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL6195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452295","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government is open to considering practicable improvements to the export licensing system for cultural goods, but has no immediate plans to make any substantive change to the current arrangements.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport has written to the noble Lord in relation to his recently proposed changes to the system and is grateful for his correspondence on this matter.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-24T14:39:20.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452295/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452295/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-11","Art Works: Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they are giving, and on what timescale, to the drawing up of proposals for substantial change to the current arrangements for export licensing for nationally important works of art.","true","Biography information for Lord Smith of Finsbury",,"Lord Smith of Finsbury","HL6196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452296","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-23","<p>Member houses of the Historic Houses Association make an important contribution to the UK's tourism industry. They attract over 24 million visits per year with a total visitor spend of £1bn; and support 41,000 jobs.</p><p> </p><p>Government has made no specific assessment of the possible closures of these historic houses. DCMS continues to work with the HHA and others, including the Heritage Lottery Fund, to support privately owned heritage.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-23T12:37:26.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452296/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452296/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-11","Historic Buildings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Historic Housing Association report, <i>The Economic and Social Contribution of Independently Owned Historic Houses and Gardens</i>, what assessment they have made of the possible closure of 70 historic buildings over the next five years, and what, if any, steps they are taking to support those business during this period.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevenson of Balmacara",,"Lord Stevenson of Balmacara","HL6197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452297","Department for Education","false","2016-02-18","<p>Under the Academies Act 2010 an academy is a charitable company limited by guarantee and is therefore required under the Companies Act 2006 to have members and a board of trustees/ directors.</p><p> </p><p>In a Multi-Academy Trust (MAT), individual academies do not have a separate legal identity and are all under the control of the trust board. Whether the board establishes local governing boards for each academy or local governing bodies to oversee groups of academies, and the range of functions delegated to any such boards, are both a matter for the board to determine – but in all cases the board remains accountable for all the academies in the MAT.</p><p> </p><p>Fewer, higher quality and more highly skilled boards overseeing groups of schools is central to the Government’s strategy for improving the quality of governance. It is also the key to schools realising a wide range of other financial and educational benefits. While every academy may not therefore have its own governing body, our guidance in the Governance Handbook makes clear that boards should have meaningful and effective arrangements in place for engaging with and listening to the views and needs of parents, staff and the wider local community.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-18T15:19:53.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452297/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452297/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Academies: Governing Bodies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to ensure that every academy has its own governing body.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452298","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>The consultation closed on 29 January. We are currently considering the responses and plan to publish the government response in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-23T14:41:06.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452298/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452298/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","English Baccalaureate","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they plan to take following their consultation on the EBacc.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452299","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>Gifts may be accepted in line with the provisions of the Ministerial Code</p><p>Retention and disposal arrangements are a matter for individual Departments. Departments may dispose of gifts after a suitable period of time has elapsed.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-02-25T17:44:52.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452299/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452299/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-11","Ministers: Official Gifts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what happens to gifts that ministers receive in their official capacity; where they are kept; and how they are eventually disposed of.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452300","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>Helping all young people, regardless of background, to get the inspiration and guidance they need for success in working life is a key part of this Government’s commitment to delivering real social justice.</p><p> </p><p>Later this year, the Department for Education will publish a comprehensive careers strategy, outlining this Government’s plans for improving careers provision by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The work of The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company, an initiative by the Department, is vital in transforming careers and enterprise provision in schools and colleges. The Company has launched its £5 million Careers and Enterprise Fund to scale good ideas and fill gaps in provision as well as rolling out its Enterprise Adviser Network; a programme connecting employees from firms of all sizes to schools through a network of enterprise advisers drawn from business volunteers</p><p> </p><p>Over the course of this Parliament, we are committing a total of £70m to our strategy to continue to transform the quality of the careers education, advice and guidance offered to young people.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-25T17:51:29.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452300/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452300/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Schools: Vocational Guidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to produce a strategy for careers education in schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452301","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>In 2014/15, 7 per cent of students[1] were entered for GCSE[2] Music as published in the latest “Revised GCSE and equivalents results in England” statistical first release (SFR)[3]. In 2009/10, the percentage of students who were entered for GCSE Music was 7 per cent.</p><p>The percentage of students[4] who were entered for A level[5] Music was 2.5 per cent which can be calculated from data published on entries in A Level Music in the latest “A level and other Level 3 results” SFR[6].</p><p>[1] Pupils at the end of key stage 4.</p><p>[2] GCSE only.</p><p>[3] Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2014 to 2015.</p><p>[4] Based on total number of entries in A level music divided by the number of students entered for at least one A level or applied single/double award A level - so could be an overestimate if a student has entered A level music more than once.</p><p>[5] A level only.</p><p>[6] A level and other level 3 results: 2014 to 2015 (revised).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-25T12:12:29.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452301/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452301/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Music: Qualifications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of pupils sat GCSE and A Level Music in 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452302","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>Teachers may choose to leave the profession for a variety of reasons. The Teacher Supply Model estimates the number of recruits required based on factors such as teachers leaving the profession. The Department is actively tackling issues that most often lead teachers to consider leaving, such as workload and poor pupil behaviour.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-02-23T14:57:55.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452302/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452302/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Teachers: Resignations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any research has been carried out into the reasons for teachers leaving the profession, in the light of the cost to the public purse of training teachers.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452303","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>We remain deeply concerned by Hamas' attempts to rearm and its efforts to rebuild infrastructure, including the tunnel network in Gaza. We are clear that Hamas and other militant groups in Gaza must permanently end rocket fire and other attacks against Israel. Any Hamas rearmament undermines efforts to improve the situation in Gaza and harms prospects for peace and stability in the Middle East.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-24T13:08:20.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452303/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452303/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recent statements by Ismael Haniyeh, a Hamas leader, that they are rebuilding tunnels from Gaza with the intention of attacking Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Turnberg",,"Lord Turnberg","HL6204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452304","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-18","<p>The UK and the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia have a long history of defence co-operation and this involves an ongoing defence engagement relationship.</p><p>In addition, we have deployed a small number of military personnel serving as liaison officers in Saudi headquarters to provide insight into Saudi operations in Yemen. These liaison officers are not involved in the targeting process - whether it be selection, decision-making or directing.</p><p>The first of these liaison officers was deployed in May 2015.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-02-18T14:51:57.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452304/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452304/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when British military liaison began with Saudi Arabia regarding its intervention in Yemen.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL6205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452305","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>We remain concerned about any damage to cultural property in Yemen and are aware of reports of alleged damage by actors in the conflict. Yemen and many members of the Saudi-led coalition are parties to the 1954 Hague Convention on the Protection of Cultural Property in the event of Armed Conflict and to the 1972 World Heritage Convention. We have raised our concerns regarding protection of cultural property with both the Government of Yemen and the Saudi Arabian government.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL6208","2016-02-23T13:37:32.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452305/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452305/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether UK advisers have highlighted to the government of Saudi Arabia the status of Yemeni cultural heritage, including the list of sites provided by the International Committee of the Blue Shield to the Ministry of Defence.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL6206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452306","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-18","<p>All UK Service personnel receive mandatory annual training in the Law of Armed Conflict and this includes training in cultural protection. They will also receive further training prior to their deployment.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-02-18T14:52:38.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452306/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452306/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether UK military personnel trained in, or dedicated to, cultural protection have been involved in liaison with Saudi Arabia regarding its intervention in Yemen.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL6207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452307","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>We remain concerned about any damage to cultural property in Yemen and are aware of reports of alleged damage by actors in the conflict. Yemen and many members of the Saudi-led coalition are parties to the 1954 Hague Convention on the Protection of Cultural Property in the event of Armed Conflict and to the 1972 World Heritage Convention. We have raised our concerns regarding protection of cultural property with both the Government of Yemen and the Saudi Arabian government.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL6206","2016-02-23T13:37:32.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452307/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452307/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what response they have made to the destruction and damage to cultural heritage sites in Yemen by the Saudi Arabian-led intervention, including the destruction of the Old City of Sana'a, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL6208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452308","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The anti-lobbying policy will apply to all government-funded grants, including those grants issued by the Arts Council England which are funded through the exchequer. It will not be applied to ACE grants funded through the National Lottery, which is allocated and ring-fenced to support statutory good causes. The policy does not however prevent any organisation from using their own self-generated funds as they see fit, and we are clear that it is not the intention to restrict the creative activities of any organisation.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-29T12:16:44.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452308/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452308/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-11","Arts: Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether arts organisations registered as charities receiving grants for arts purposes through bodies such as the Arts Council England will be exempt from their new policy restricting how such grants may be used; and if not, what assessment they have made of whether their new policy is compatible with the arm's length principle of the funding of the arts.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL6209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452309","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The anti-lobbying policy covers exchequer-funded grants and does not cover Lottery funding. Arts Council England grants, funded through the National Lottery, are allocated and ring-fenced to support statutory good causes.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-29T12:17:28.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452309/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452309/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-11","Arts: Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether arts organisations registered as charities receiving grants for arts purposes provided through National Lottery funding will be subject to the new government policy restricting how such grants may be used.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL6210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452310","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-25","<p>The independent review of Local Council Tax Support Schemes commenced on the 2 December 2015. The chair, Eric Ollerenshaw OBE, put out a public call for evidence which was announced and promoted in our press release of the same date. The public call for evidence ran from the 2 December 2015 to 12 January 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-02-25T14:55:00.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452310/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452310/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-11","Local Council Tax Support Schemes Independent Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that individuals affected by the abolition of Council Tax Benefit are made aware of their review of that policy and encouraged to participate in it.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL6211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452311","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Independent Review of Local Council Tax Support schemes will report by 31 March and will reflect the views and data submitted to the Chair. The Department does not currently intend to publish individual submissions to protect the confidentiality of those who submitted evidence.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-02-25T14:55:37.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452311/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452311/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-11","Local Council Tax Support Schemes Independent Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will place in the Library of the House the submissions to their review of local Council Tax Support, and the data they collected from local authorities to help inform that review.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL6212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452312","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>The changes as introduced to the House of Commons on 9<sup>th</sup> July 2015 would mean that existing claimants, whether in the work-related activity group or the support group, who undergo a work capability assessment after April 2017 and are placed in, or remain in, the work-related activity group, will continue to receive the work-related activity component.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Freud","HL6214 ; HL6215","2016-02-25T15:13:50.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452312/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452312/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under the provisions of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, a claimant receiving Employment and Support Allowance work-related activity component prior to April 2017 who is reassessed after April 2017 but still found to be entitled to the work-related activity component would have their benefit reduced to the level of Jobseeker's Allowance.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL6213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452313","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>The changes as introduced to the House of Commons on 9<sup>th</sup> July 2015 would mean that existing claimants, whether in the work-related activity group or the support group, who undergo a work capability assessment after April 2017 and are placed in, or remain in, the work-related activity group, will continue to receive the work-related activity component.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Freud","HL6213 ; HL6215","2016-02-25T15:13:51.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452313/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452313/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under the provisions of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, a claimant receiving Employment and Support Allowance support component prior to April 2017 who is reassessed after April 2017 and moved to the work-related activity group would have their benefit reduced to the level of Jobseeker's Allowance.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL6214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452314","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>The changes as introduced to the House of Commons on 9<sup>th</sup> July 2015 would mean that existing claimants, whether in the work-related activity group or the support group, who undergo a work capability assessment after April 2017 and are placed in, or remain in, the work-related activity group, will continue to receive the work-related activity component.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Freud","HL6213 ; HL6214","2016-02-25T15:13:51.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452314/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452314/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under the provisions of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, a claimant receiving Employment and Support Allowance prior to April 2017 who had to re-apply after April 2017 due to a change in their condition would have their benefit reduced to the level of Jobseeker's Allowance if they were found to be entitled to the work-related activity component.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL6215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452315","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-25","<p>I refer the noble Lady to my answer to her on 26 November 2015, PQ HL4002. The Social Housing Regulator is statutorily independent. The Secretary of State cannot, therefore, intervene in this matter. Details of the Social Housing Regulator's complaints procedure can be found (attached) at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/how-to-appeal-against-our-decisions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/how-to-appeal-against-our-decisions</a>. As with all public bodies, if there are grounds the Regulator can be challenged through the courts.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-02-25T16:10:05.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452315/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452315/answer","160224 Social Housing Regulators complaints procedure HL6216.doc","160224 Social Housing Regulators complaints procedure HL6216.doc","Social Housing Regulators's complaints procedure","Social Housing Regulators's complaints procedure","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452315/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-11","Circle Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 1 February (HL5321), what statutory powers the Secretary of State has to intervene if the Homes and Communities Agency regulator is found to be failing in its responsibility to ensure that Circle Housing Group is properly managing its gas safety and repairs contractor.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL6216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452316","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>The information is not collected by the Department.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-25T12:12:02.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452316/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452316/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-11","Doctors: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what research they have undertaken into the percentage of female medical students who after qualification (1) never work as doctors, (2) cease to work as doctors after five years, (3) cease to work as doctors after 10 years, and (4) only work part-time after 10 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL6217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452317","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>This data is not collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service publish the following information, <em>Acceptances by Detailed subject group and sex,</em> which is also available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ucas.com/sites/default/files/eoc_data_resource_2015-dr3_019_01.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ucas.com/sites/default/files/eoc_data_resource_2015-dr3_019_01.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Number of acceptances by Cycle Year</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Subject Group: Pre-Clinical Medicine</p></td><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>3,415</p></td><td><p>3,500</p></td><td><p>3,595</p></td><td><p>3,545</p></td><td><p>3,575</p></td><td><p>3,645</p></td><td><p>3,380</p></td><td><p>3,400</p></td><td><p>3,360</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>4,430</p></td><td><p>4,515</p></td><td><p>4,385</p></td><td><p>4,405</p></td><td><p>4,220</p></td><td><p>4,160</p></td><td><p>4,135</p></td><td><p>4,280</p></td><td><p>4,300</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This is for the United Kingdom.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-25T12:11:44.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452317/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452317/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-11","Doctors: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of gender equality in medical school entrants.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL6218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452318","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-24","<p>Waste water re-injection in the US has been linked to seismic activity, but this technique has not been proposed in the UK and the Environment Agency will not permit re-injection of waste water into any formation at this stage.</p><p> </p><p>In the UK, we have over 50 years’ experience regulating the onshore oil and gas industry. Our regulator regime is robust and we have strong controls in place to mitigate the risk of any seismic activity in the UK.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-02-24T14:40:06.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452318/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452318/answer","DECC_infographic_Traffic-light-system_finaldec13.pdf","DECC_infographic_Traffic-light-system_finaldec13.pdf","DECC: Traffic light system","DECC: Traffic light system","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452318/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Fracking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the light of the experience in Oklahoma in the US, they plan to commission a detailed study into the potential correlation between fracking in the UK and more frequent earthquakes.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL6219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452319","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-24","<p>Improving the quality of our air and reducing carbon emissions are important priorities for Her Majesty's Government. Later this year we will be publishing detailed plans on how we will deliver against Carbon Budgets, including information about how these measures can also support air quality objectives. Further information on the synergies across these policy objectives was outlined in DEFRA’s air quality plan, <em>Improving Air Quality in the UK - tackling nitrogen dioxide in our towns and cities</em>, December 2015.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-02-24T14:40:50.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452319/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452319/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether their policy for reducing carbon emissions in the UK over the next five years is consistent with their policy for reducing the average concentration of air pollution, and whether they will publish data relevant to that assessment.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL6220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452326","Attorney General","false","2016-02-22","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer I gave to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=24782" target="_blank">24782</a> from the Hon. Member for Coventry South (Jim Cunningham) on the 4<sup>th</sup> February 2016.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","27075","2016-02-22T10:29:24.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452326/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452326/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-11","Department for Education: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, if he will estimate the costs attributed to the Department for Education by the Government Legal Department in the 2014-15 financial year.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","27074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452327","Attorney General","false","2016-02-22","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer I gave to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=24782" target="_blank">24782</a> from the Hon. Member for Coventry South (Jim Cunningham) on the 4<sup>th</sup> February 2016.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","27074","2016-02-22T10:29:24.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452327/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452327/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-11","Department for Education: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, if he will estimate the costs attributed to the Department for Education for cases relating to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 by the Government Legal Department in the 2014-15 financial year.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","27075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452328","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The policy framework for arms export licensing to all destinations, including Saudi Arabia, remains as set out in the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, known as the Consolidated Criteria.</p><p> </p><p>This requires all export licence applications to be carefully assessed on a case by case basis against the Consolidated Criteria, taking into account all relevant factors at the time of application, including reporting by non-Governmental organisations, the United Nations and others.</p><p> </p><p>A licence will not be issued, for any country, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the Criteria.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:12:11.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452328/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452328/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his arms export policy to Saudi Arabia of the legal advice on that matter commissioned by Amnesty International and Saferworld, published in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","27077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452329","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>My Department has carried out an assessment of the impacts of devolving the power to extend Sunday trading hours. This will be published shortly.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T18:00:02.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452329/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452329/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the potential effect on levels of employment in convenience stores of proposals to devolve Sunday trading restrictions; and what the evidential basis for that estimate was.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","27069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452330","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>My Department has carried out an assessment of the impacts of devolving the power to extend Sunday trading hours and this will be published shortly.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:41:09.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452330/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452330/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on the profit of convenience stores of proposals to devolve Sunday trading restrictions; and what the evidential basis for that estimate was.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","27070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452331","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The six petitions referenced in that paragraph were locally organised petitions which we believe were arranged by individuals. These were in addition to the national campaigns organised by the Christian Institute, the Association of Convenience Stores (ACS) and CitizenGo.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:33:58.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452331/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452331/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to paragraph 2.9 of Devolving Sunday Trading Rules: government response, published in February 2016, from which organised campaigns the six petitions were received.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452332","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government received 7,171 responses to the consultation, though a significantly smaller number used the standard online consultation form and addressed the questions directly.</p><p> </p><p>USDAW responded to the consultation and its representatives met with officials during the course of the consultation. USDAW answered no to Question 1 in the consultation.</p><p> </p><p>TUC and the National Union of General and Municipal Workers (GMB) also responded to the consultation and their representatives met with officials during the course of the consultation. UNISON responded to the consultation but did not meet with officials. All three (100%) responded no to Question 1 in the consultation.</p><p> </p><p>ACS responded to the consultation and its representatives met with officials during the course of the consultation answered no to Question 1 in the consultation.</p><p>The department does not hold full data from this consultation broken down by respondent type as a large portion of respondents chose to respond in their own words rather than addressing the consultation questions directly, and/or did not indicate the type of organisation they represented.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T10:04:42.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452332/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452332/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Sunday Trading: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations were received from (a) USDAW, (b) other trade unions, (c) ACS and (d) other trade and workers' associations in response to the government's consultation, Devolving Sunday trading rules, published on 5 August 2015; and what (i) number and (ii) proportion of those respondents answered (A) yes, (B) no and (C) otherwise to Question 1 in that consultation.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","27030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452333","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Savings will broadly be delivered through implementing a new digital infrastructure to provide cost-effective access to export services; contractual efficiencies; and prioritising market and sector opportunities that will add most value to UK export levels. This is about being more efficient and delivering for UK businesses, including through enhancing direct support and developing the private sector market.</p><p>HM Treasury has recognised the importance of the exports agenda by agreeing that £175m of further proposed savings between 2016-17 and 2019-20 should be reinvested in priority areas. The Government is committed to driving a step-change in UK exports and the reinvestment secured to refocus UK Trade &amp; Investment will help us deliver this.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-26T11:35:44.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452333/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452333/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","UK Trade and Investment: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on levels of exports of changes in the budget of UK Trade and Investment between 2015 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","27039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452334","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Government amendments to Clause 12 (Facility Time Reporting) and Clause 13 (Facility Time cap) of the Trade Union Bill were included in the Bill at Lords Committee.</p><p> </p><p>The remaining stages in the Lords are amending stages and the Government will table amendments as necessary.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-21T15:24:25.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452334/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452334/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, further to the oral contribution of the Minister for Skills of 2 February 2016, Official Report, column 776, whether his Department intends to bring forward amendments relating to check-off and facilities time before the Trade Union Bill reaches Report Stage in the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","26990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452335","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>Innovation is a key driver of productivity and the UK ranks among the best in the world in various indices. The Government is focussed on creating the best conditions for innovative businesses to flourish and will be protecting, in cash terms, total spending on business led innovation through Innovate UK.</p><p> </p><p>We are exploring the range of finance products, including loans, available in a number of other countries. We will also be conducting market research to engage with, and further understand the needs of, innovative businesses in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also intends to commence pilots to test specific finance products before progressing to full roll out.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-22T17:26:26.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452335/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452335/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Business: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on UK productivity of the planned introduction of research and development grants.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","26996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452336","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Government supports the use of the lesser duty rule in trade defence cases, as it allows for protection against unfair trade while at the same time avoiding the imposition of disproportionate costs on the wider economy. We do not support changes that would lessen its effectiveness as a trade defence instrument.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:21:32.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452336/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452336/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Antidumping Duties: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of amending trade defence instruments to add a further exemption to the lesser duty rules in cases of social and environmental dumping.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","27111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452337","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-06","<p>There have been no conversations between the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Secretary of State for Education on the subjects above.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-06T10:14:28.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452337/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452337/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the publication, entitled The Department for Education review, published in November 2012, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Education on the potential benefits of departmental regional office bases to the delivery of his Department's policies.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452338","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Department intends to close the Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place by January 2018. This intention is based on the strategic vision for the Department by 2020 that seeks to save 30-40% of its operating costs, reduce the number of locations it operates from (from currently around 80 to 7 centres and a regional footprint for the provision of local services), and halves the number of its Partner Organisations.</p><p> </p><p>The location strategy is based on the need to simplify delivery and focus expertise in specific areas. This includes locating the policy function in one place, close to Ministers, in the HQ in London. This decision was based on on-going analysis and discussions, leading to the decision by the Executive Board.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-22T17:15:59.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452338/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452338/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish the cost-benefit analysis related to his Department's decision to close its Sheffield office.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452339","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Since summer 2015 the Department has been reviewing its business model. By 2020, we want to simplify our structure, become more digital, be cheaper for taxpayers and better for users. As part of this we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint for the provision of local services. The intention to close the BIS Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place is based on a strategy to simplify delivery and focus expertise in specific areas. Consistent with this strategy the policy function will be in one place, close to Ministers, and the Department has made a decision to locate all its policy functions in the HQ in London. By 2020 the majority of employees in BIS and our Partner Organisations will continue to be based outside of London.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-22T17:10:06.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452339/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452339/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business,  Innovation and Skills: Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the benefits to his Department of conducting policy work outside of London.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452340","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The intention to close the BIS Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place is subject to consultation with the Departmental Trade Unions. These are taking place now and, therefore, it is not possible to estimate how many staff will relocate to London or leave the Department.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-09T15:40:05.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452340/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452340/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many people he estimates will (a) relocate to London and (b) leave his Department following the announcement to close his Department's Sheffield office.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452341","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The intention to close the BIS Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place is based on our strategy to simplify our delivery and focus expertise in specific areas over five years to 2020. Therefore, our policy function needs to be in one place, close to Ministers, and the Department made a decision to locate all our policy functions in the HQ in London. Other decisions around our estates will be taken in due course and will, of course, be subject to consultation. We therefore cannot give an estimate of when all decisions on the Department’s estate will be concluded.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-22T17:28:18.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452341/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452341/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he expects all final decisions on his Department's estate relating to the implementation of the BIS 2020 strategy to be concluded.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452342","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The ONS analysed the impact of the short term Olympic relaxation of the Sunday trading rules and found that it was not possible to make any inference from the data. They found no definite pattern amongst the growth rates of retail sales and noted that other factors, such as the weather and time of year, will have impacted sales.</p><p> </p><p>In formulating its final proposals, the Government has carefully considered all the evidence submitted during the consultation process.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:57:09.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452342/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452342/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of the 2012 temporary liberalisation of Sunday trading regulations on its proposals for the devolution of such regulations to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","27080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452343","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-08","<p>My Department has a total of 45 extant video conferencing facilities in place in 12 of its locations in England, Scotland and Wales. The investment costs of those facilities are as detailed below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p><strong>Total for 5 years</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Investment costs</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£599,144</p></td><td><p>£213,752</p></td><td><p>£82,887</p></td><td><p>£85,821</p></td><td><p>£981,604</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-08T17:33:37.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452343/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452343/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what investment his Department has made in video-conferencing facilities in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452344","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-23","<p>Responsibility for considering competition issues in the UK falls to the independent competition authorities. Since 2014 this role has been carried out by the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA).</p><p> </p><p>The Office of Fair Trading (OFT), the predecessor of the CMA, conducted a detailed investigation of the operation of the distribution arrangements for the supply of newspapers and magazines in England and Wales over a number of years. In September 2009, the OFT decided that, although there might be competition concerns, developments benefiting consumers could come about from industry parties self-assessing their distribution agreements following competition guidance provided by the OFT.</p><p> </p><p>The OFT considered that it would not be feasible for the Competition Commission to obtain the necessary evidence at that time properly to assess how the supply chains were likely to evolve in the short term. This decision was reviewed and confirmed in March 2012 and was upheld by the Competition Appeal Tribunal in October 2012.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-23T16:45:30.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452344/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452344/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Newspaper Press: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent assessment he has made of the extent of anti-competitive practices in the newspaper wholesale market.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","27103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452345","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>Video conferencing is used across the Department as a tool for keeping in touch with colleagues split across numerous sites, with around 1,500 meetings held by video-conferencing every month. <br></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-29T10:26:45.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452345/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452345/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of investing in video-conferencing facilities to facilitate split-site working by staff in his Department.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452346","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Department of Business, Innovation and Skills does not hold that information centrally. To gather and analyse this information would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-26T14:57:54.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452346/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452346/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff in his Department have relocated (a) out of London and (b) into London in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452347","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-23","<p>Subject to consultation, the Department intends to close the Sheffield office at St. Paul’s Place by January 2018. This intention is based on the strategic vision for the Department that seeks to save 30-40% of its operating costs, reduce the number of locations it operates from (from currently around 80 to 7 centres and a regional footprint for the provision of local services), and halve the number of its Partner Organisations by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Intention is subject to consultation, to close the Sheffield office by January 2018. This gives us time to transition the policy roles affected.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","27099","2016-02-23T15:41:53.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452347/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452347/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the closure of his Department's Sheffield office on the delivery of his Department's policies.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452348","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-23","<p>Subject to consultation, the Department intends to close the Sheffield office at St. Paul’s Place by January 2018. This intention is based on the strategic vision for the Department that seeks to save 30-40% of its operating costs, reduce the number of locations it operates from (from currently around 80 to 7 centres and a regional footprint for the provision of local services), and halve the number of its Partner Organisations by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Intention is subject to consultation, to close the Sheffield office by January 2018. This gives us time to transition the policy roles affected.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","27098","2016-02-23T15:41:53.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452348/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452348/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect on his Department's policy expertise and experience in the development of (a) higher and (b) further education of the closure of his Department's Sheffield office.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452349","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The intention to close the BIS Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place is based on our strategy to simplify our delivery and focus expertise in specific areas over five years to 2020. Therefore, our policy function needs to be in one place, close to Ministers, and the Department made a decision to locate all our policy functions in the HQ in London. Other decisions around our estates will be taken in due course and will, of course, be subject to consultation. We therefore cannot give an estimate of when all decisions on the Department’s estate will be concluded.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-26T14:20:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452349/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452349/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which offices outside London he does not plan to close under the BIS 2020 strategy.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452350","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>A key part of the Government’s commitment of 3 million apprenticeships starts in England by 2020 is to ensure that quality apprenticeships are available at all levels and in all sectors. This will give people the widest opportunity to participate in high quality programmes to improve their skills and give employers, including charities and voluntary organisations, the skilled workforce they need to grow and improve productivity.</p><p> </p><p>The apprenticeships levy will only be paid by those with an annual pay bill of more than £3 million. This is 2% of all employers. We will continue to engage with charity and voluntary sectors in the development and implementation of the apprenticeship levy.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:00:24.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452350/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452350/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the apprenticeship levy on the charity and voluntary sectors.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","27184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452351","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Institute for Apprenticeships (IfA) will have a very small research role, focused around its tight set of core functions. It will not continue the UKCES function of carrying out research into the wider labour market.</p><p> </p><p>BIS has consulted the Devolved Administrations and other users of labour market information on future research priorities. These discussions have identified the significance of the Employer Skills Survey, the Employer Perspectives Survey and the LMI (Labour Market Information) for All Portal. We are considering how these can best be delivered in future and will announce future arrangements as soon as final decisions are made.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:02:05.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452351/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452351/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","UK Commission for Employment and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of transferring staff from the UK Commission for Employment and Skills to the Institute for Apprentices to allow continuity of collected labour market information when government funding for that commission ceases in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","27185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452352","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Institute for Apprenticeships (IFA) will have a role in advising Government on which funding cap each apprenticeship standard should be allocated to.</p><p> </p><p>The IFA will take into account the cost of apprenticeship training and assessment as well as the demand for different skills across the economy.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:05:44.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452352/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452352/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will put mechanisms in place to ensure that the Institute for Apprentices responds to labour market information when setting funding cap levels for apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","27186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452353","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>Since the answer of 20 October 2015, the Government has been carefully considering the issues raised in the consultation, and plans to publish the Impact Assessment, including results of the family test, shortly.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:38:18.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452353/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452353/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2015 to Question 12101, for what reasons the Family Test assessment on Sunday trading has not yet been published; when he expects that assessment to be published; and if he will ensure that that assessment is published before consideration of new clauses in the Enterprise Bill [Lords].","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","27189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452354","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-26","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my answer of 1<sup>st</sup> February 2016, Written Question No. 23775. <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-22/23775/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-22/23775/</a>]</p><p> </p><p>In addition, while speaking in Westminster Hall on 25<sup>th</sup> January 2016, I assured the House that HM Revenue and Customs would produce an initial draft impact assessment alongside the formal consultation process, which will start this spring. As with any other tax measure, a detailed assessment of the impact on administrative burdens will be published alongside draft legislation.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-26T12:06:49.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452354/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452354/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-11","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has conducted an impact assessment on proposals to require small businesses and self-employed people to complete quarterly digital tax returns by 2020.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","27148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452355","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>The provision of its Crown branches is the commercial responsibility of Post Office Limited.</p><p>Like any commercial organisation, Post Office Limited continually reviews all elements of its business to ensure they are effective and efficient. Changes are essential to ensure the long term viability and competitiveness of any company, whether these are as part of a dedicated transformation programme or in the normal course of operations.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-26T12:54:20.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452355/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452355/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons changes to Crown branches take place outside the scope of formal Crown transformation programmes.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","27153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452356","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>A key part of the Government’s commitment of 3 million apprenticeships starts in England by 2020 is to ensure that quality apprenticeships are available at all levels and in all sectors. This will give people the widest opportunity to participate in high quality programmes to improve their skills and give employers, including universities, the skilled workforce they need to grow and improve productivity.</p><p> </p><p>We are encouraging employers to take the lead in developing more apprenticeship standards at degree level. This will create a business opportunity for universities, many of which are already working with employers to design apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T16:58:41.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452356/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452356/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the apprenticeship levy on universities.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","27181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452357","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>The UK, through DFID, is encouraging UK companies to improve working conditions, safety standards and pay in the garment sector in Bangladesh in a number of ways. The UK has used every opportunity to call for companies to take responsibility for the working conditions. This has included a Westminster Hall debate, repeat Ministerial visits to Bangladesh, and various meetings with retailers and buyers.</p><p>The UK Government has also encouraged all UK Brands to sign up to the Bangladesh Safety Accord, an independent and legally-binding agreement between trade unions and private companies that was established in the wake of the Rana Plaza disaster to improve safety and health standards in the Bangladeshi Ready-Made Garment Industry. A total of 30 UK companies have signed the Accord.</p><p>The UK is also supporting the Trade in Global Value Chains Initiative (TGVCI) which supports UK companies to invest more in their supply chains and improve working conditions in the factories in which they are working. DFID also supports the Ethical Trading Initiative (ETI) which is a leading alliance of British companies, trade unions and non-governmental organisations working together to improve the lives of workers around the world.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-25T13:43:19.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452357/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452357/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Bangladesh: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to encourage UK companies to improve (a) working conditions, (b) safety standards and (c) pay in clothes factories in Bangladesh in their supply chains.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452358","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The UK Commission for Employment and Skills’ (UKCES) work over the last parliament has helped in setting the skills agenda for the future; and their activities have created the conditions to move to the next phase of more devolution, greater employer ownership and the apprenticeship levy. We have, however, concluded that we need new structures to move onto that next phase and have announced the establishment in England of a new Institute for Apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p>In light of this, a decision was taken as part of the spending review by Whitehall Departments to withdraw funding from UKCES during 2016-17 in the context of the need to make savings in non-participation budgets to allow the core adult skills participation budgets to be protected in cash terms.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:46:57.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452358/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452358/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","UK Commission for Employment and Skills: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons he has decided to withdraw funding from the UK Commission for Employment and Skills; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","27196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452359","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Commissioners of the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UKCES) were not consulted during the spending review process prior to the decision taken by Whitehall Departments to withdraw funding.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has subsequently been working closely with the UKCES’s Strategic Management Group of Commissioners to manage the implications of the decision.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:07:13.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452359/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452359/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","UK Commission for Employment and Skill: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he consulted the board of the UK Commission for Employment and Skills prior to his decision to withdraw its funding.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","27197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452360","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has been in regular contact with the Devolved Administrations both at Ministerial and official level since the spending review decision by Whitehall Departments to withdraw funding from the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UKCES).</p><p> </p><p>A meeting of senior officials took place on 20th January and Ministers met on 4th February. These meetings discussed common issues within the UK’s devolved skills systems, including the implications of the decision on UKCES funding. At working level, officials in all Governments involved the work of UKCES are meeting regularly to discuss and agree the necessary transition arrangements that will be required as a result of the withdrawal of funding.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:08:38.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452360/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452360/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","UK Commission for Employment and Skill: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he has received form the governments of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland on his decision to withdraw funding from the UK Commission for Employment and Skills.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","27198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452361","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>I refer the hon Member to the reply to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-02-04/25901/" target="_blank">25901</a>.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-22T17:31:22.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452361/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452361/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","UK Commission for Employment and Skill: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he plans to take to collect data on trends in the UK labour market after funding is withdrawn from the UK Commission for Employment and Skills.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","27199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452362","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-22T15:36:52.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452362/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452362/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-11","Charities: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which charities have used government grants to pay for campaigns in (a) 2014-15 and (b) 2015-16 to date; what the nature of each such campaign was; what estimate he has made of the amount of government funding used for each such campaign; and which such charities have been asked to repay part of their grant on the grounds that such expenditure was outwith the terms and conditions of that grant.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","27174"
