"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452399","Department for Education","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Department has contracted 92 suppliers to provide education specialist contractors to support the academies and free school programme. Further details can be found in Annex G of the supplementary evidence submitted to the Education Select Committee on the role of RSCs, which can be found here:</p><p><a href="http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/education-committee/the-role-of-regional-schools-commissioners/written/25134.html" target="_blank">http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/education-committee/the-role-of-regional-schools-commissioners/written/25134.html</a></p><p> </p><p>In financial year 2014-15, the Department spent £1,112,580.53 on education specialist contractors to support the regional school commissioners.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-26T14:48:45.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452399/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452399/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many specialist contractors hired by her Department to advise regional school commissioners there are; and how much her Department spent on such contractors in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452400","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>The specialist contractors that support the academies and free school programme are directed in advance of commencing any work that their conduct and behaviour when delivering the Department’s business complies with the Civil Service Code’s principles.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-25T11:03:59.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452400/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452400/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what training is provided to specialist contractors hired by her Department to advise regional school commissioners on their responsibilities related to the Civil Service Code.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452401","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>The department does not publish daily rates for specialist contractors. Doing so would prejudice commercial interests.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-25T11:05:55.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452401/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452401/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the daily rate of pay is for specialist contractors hired by her Department to advise regional school commissioners.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452402","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Department will publish an award notice on GOV.UK that names suppliers that have been awarded contracts, business addresses and contract values over £20,000. The Department will also be publishing related supplier contracts that support the academy and free school programme on Contract Finder on GOV.UK by 31 March 2016.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","27023","2016-02-25T11:06:17.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452402/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452402/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which specialist contractors her Department has hired to advise regional school commissioners.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452403","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>Contractors procured to support the academies and free schools programme are required to declare conflicts of interest.</p><p>The contract states, “The Contractor is required to declare to the Contract Manager any interests and/or links, including other contracts or positions held whether they be paid or unpaid or relationships with, but not limited to, schools, education providers or other external organisations involved in the provision of education or education services so the Contract Manager may assess whether any conflicts of interest, whether potential, actual or perceived, and as reasonably judged by the Contract Manager, may have the potential to present reputational, operational or legal or risks to the Contractor and to the Department in allocating any particular project.</p><p>&quot;If such a conflict of interest does arise, or may arise, the Contractor will declare it to the Department immediately and accept that the Department may ask the Contractor to immediately cease any involvement with the task giving rise to the conflict.”</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-25T11:07:07.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452403/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452403/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the specialist contractors hired by her Department to advise regional school commissioners are required to declare any interests relevant to their employment by her Department.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452404","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>The regional school commissioners currently have one agency worker and one inward secondee from a County Council.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-25T11:07:24.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452404/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452404/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff in the office of each regional schools commissioners are employed under a contract of employment to another third party.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452405","Department for Education","false","2016-02-22","<p>We are considering the findings of the National Audit Office report on training new teachers. The Permanent Secretary and Sinead O’Sullivan, Director of Programme Delivery in the National College for Teaching and Leadership, will be appearing as witnesses before a Public Accounts Committee hearing on the report on Monday 7 March 2016. This will be an opportunity to discuss the content of the report.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-22T17:21:19.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452405/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452405/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the implications for her Department's policies on training teachers of the findings of the National Audit Office report, Training new teachers, published in February 2016.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","27027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452406","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>The national curriculum sets out the expectation that pupils should be provided with opportunities to engage in a broad range of competitive sports and activities.</p><p>Many national governing bodies of sports and elite sporting organisations offer a programme for schools, to engage children and young people in their sports. Through their school sports programme, the Premier League is currently working in over 4,000 schools to support the PE curriculum, provide sports clubs, and deliver enrichment activities. In October 2015, the Premier League announced that they will expand their schools offer to every primary school in the country within 6 years.</p><p>The Department funds ‘On the Front Foot’, a programme designed and delivered by Premiership Rugby to develop character and resilience in primary and secondary schools across the country. The programme delivers classroom based and physical activity character building programmes to 17,250 pupils.</p><p>The Football Association’s Skills programme is a nationwide football coaching programme working in over 1,000 primary schools a year, providing specialist football coaching for children and supporting teachers in their delivery of sport. Sessions are offered during PE lessons, extra-curricula clubs and holiday clubs.</p><p>The Tennis Foundation and the Lawn Tennis Association support teachers with training, resource and equipment to help them deliver tennis in schools. Their aim is to increase access to tennis across schools, further and higher education through a wide range of programmes. They offer support to make tennis inclusive and accessible to all pupils. Over 60,000 primary, special and secondary school pupils take part in schools tennis competitions every year.</p><p>The Rugby Football Union works with hundreds of maintained schools as part of its ‘All Schools Plan’ to help more secondary school children play rugby. This was launched by the RFU and the Rugby Football Foundation in 2012, as part of the RFU’s Rugby World Cup 2015 legacy plans.</p><p>The School Games is the Government’s framework for competitive school sports. The programme provides a national final event where the most talented young people in the UK compete in 12 different sports. More than 150 of the athletes who competed at the Commonwealth Games in Glasgow had previously competed at the School Games and 59 athletes claimed 84 medals.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-23T11:27:03.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452406/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452406/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Schools: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to improve links between schools and elite sports organisations.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","27028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452407","Department for Education","false","2016-02-26","<p>Information on the proportion of schools providing at least two hours of physical education (PE) per week is not held by the Department.</p><p>Through the primary PE and sport premium, primary schools have received over £450m of ring-fenced funding to improve PE and sport. We have committed to continue this funding until 2020. In December 2015, we published a report looking at how schools used the primary PE and sport premium and the impact of the fund on PE and sports provision. Primary schools reported spending around 2 hours per week on curricular PE in both 2013/14 and 2014/15[1]. 87% of schools also reported that the quality of PE teaching had increased since the introduction of the premium.</p><p>We do not hold information on how much time is spent on curricular PE for secondary schools.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pe-and-sport-premium-an-investigation-in-primary-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pe-and-sport-premium-an-investigation-in-primary-schools</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-26T12:08:35.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452407/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452407/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Physical Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) maintained primary schools, (b) maintained secondary schools, (c) primary academies and (d) secondary academies provide at least two hours of physical education per week.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","27029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452408","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>In March 2015 the Department published a consultative statistical working paper proposing performance measures for multi-academy trusts[1].</p><p>In addition, the Department’s school performance tables now allow parents and others to more easily see which academies are within a multi-academy trust and the information for each academy, including their academic performance and Ofsted judgements[2].</p><p>Ofsted also carries out focused inspections of groups of academies within multi-academy trusts and these outcomes are published[3].</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-in-academy-chains-and-las-performance-measures" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-in-academy-chains-and-las-performance-measures</a></p><p>[2] <a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/performance/" target="_blank">http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/performance/</a></p><p>[3] <a href="http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/resources/local-authority-school-improvement-arrangements-inspections-and-focused-school-inspections" target="_blank">http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/resources/local-authority-school-improvement-arrangements-inspections-and-focused-school-inspections</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-23T10:51:28.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452408/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452408/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Academies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department plans to take to publish performance data for academy chains.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","26994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452409","Department for Education","false","2016-02-24","<p>Invitation to tender including the contract was published on contracts finder on GOV.UK on 12 August 2015 at:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/fcbd797d-c613-47f5-8853-79f2ad7d74a9" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/fcbd797d-c613-47f5-8853-79f2ad7d74a9</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-24T16:29:38.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452409/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452409/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what functions are delegated to each specialist contractor hired by her Department to advise regional school commissioners.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452410","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Department will publish an award notice on GOV.UK that names suppliers that have been awarded contracts, business addresses and contract values over £20,000. The Department will also be publishing related supplier contracts that support the academy and free school programme on Contract Finder on GOV.UK by 31 March 2016.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","27020","2016-02-25T11:06:17.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452410/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452410/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish the terms and conditions of the contracts of the specialist contractors hired by her Department to advise regional school commissioners.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452411","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>Local authorities are responsible for ensuring there are sufficient school places in their local area.</p><p>The RSCs are responsible for approving the sponsors of new free schools and intervening in underperforming academies and free schools in their area. The RSCs consider basic need when making decisions on proposed changes to academies, and must consider any representations from local authorities.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-25T11:07:50.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452411/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452411/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what duties are placed on regional school commissioners to consult with local authorities on school place planning.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452412","Department for Education","false","2016-02-25","<p>At present, each RSC office employs between 8 and 10 members of staff. In line with the Department's commitment to greater transparency, staffing structure information for each RSC office, including staff count for each grade, pay scale and location, is published on GOV.UK at: <a href="http://reference.data.gov.uk/gov-structure/organogram/?pubbod=department-for-education" target="_blank">http://reference.data.gov.uk/gov-structure/organogram/?pubbod=department-for-education</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-25T11:08:52.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452412/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452412/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the staffing complement is of the office of each regional schools commissioner; and what the staff grade is of each post in each such office.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","27026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452413","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Department does not collect data on schools which have restricted the school trips that children with autism can attend.</p><p>Public sector bodies, including maintained schools, are covered by the public sector equality duty under the Equality Act 2010. When carrying out their functions they must have regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, promote equality of opportunity and foster good relations between disabled and non-disabled children and young people. This duty is anticipatory, which means that schools must take into account the needs of disabled pupils, such as those with autism, when planning school trips and other events.</p><p>The Special Educational Needs and Disability Code of Practice: 0-25 emphasises that school leaders should establish and maintain a culture of high expectations that expects those working with children and young people with SEN or disabilities to include them in all the opportunities available to other children and young people so that they can achieve well. This would include opportunities to socialise and attend external school trips.</p><p>If parents believe that a school has discriminated against their autistic child in planning school trips, they can make a claim for disability discrimination to the First-tier Tribunal.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-23T11:55:51.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452413/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452413/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Children: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of schools which have restricted the school trips which children with autism spectrum disorder can attend in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452414","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>The number of pupils recorded as having a mental health condition who received a permanent or fixed period exclusion is not held by the Department.</p><p>The number and proportion of pupils in national curriculum year group 10 and 11 with an autistic spectrum disorder primary need who were excluded in each of the last 5 years can be found in the attached table.</p><p>Information on the number of fixed period and permanent exclusions for all pupils, including separate breakdowns by national curriculum year group and special educational need provision, is available in the ‘Permanent and fixed-period exclusions in England’ National Statistics release[1].</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-exclusions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-exclusions</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","27054","2016-02-23T12:00:31.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452414/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452414/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Pupil Exclusions: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of pupils who were (a) permanently and (b) temporarily excluded from school were recorded as having mental health conditions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452415","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>The number of pupils recorded as having a mental health condition who received a permanent or fixed period exclusion is not held by the Department.</p><p>The number and proportion of pupils in national curriculum year group 10 and 11 with an autistic spectrum disorder primary need who were excluded in each of the last 5 years can be found in the attached table.</p><p>Information on the number of fixed period and permanent exclusions for all pupils, including separate breakdowns by national curriculum year group and special educational need provision, is available in the ‘Permanent and fixed-period exclusions in England’ National Statistics release[1].</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-exclusions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-exclusions</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","27053","2016-02-23T12:00:32.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452415/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452415/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Pupil Exclusions: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of pupils in Years 10 and 11 were (a) permanently and (b) temporarily excluded from school had autism spectrum disorder in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452416","Department for Education","false","2016-02-26","<p>Many of the findings of the report echo those reported by the Chief Schools Adjudicator in her Annual Report for the 2013/14 school year. The Government will shortly consult on a package of changes to the School Admissions Code which will both respond to concerns from parents and to the findings in the Chief Adjudicator’s Annual Report. That package will include measures to improve fairness and transparency.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-26T14:52:31.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452416/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452416/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of implications for her policies of the finding in the Fair Admissions Campaign's report, An unholy mess, published in October 2015, that schools which are their own admission authorities are consistently failing to comply with the School Admissions Code.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","27169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452417","Department for Education","false","2016-02-26","<p>We are currently considering what possible changes it would be appropriate to make to the School Admissions Code to support parents and schools, in addition to those that we have already announced. We will conduct a full public consultation in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-26T14:45:44.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452417/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452417/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to her Department's press release, Parents to get greater say in the school admissions process of 25 January 2016, when her Department plans to launch its consultation on proposed revisions to the School Admissions Code.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","27147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452418","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>Until a decision has been made, the Department does not wish to name both schools in order to protect the Secretary of State’s decision making powers when considering whether to give consent.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-23T12:03:51.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452418/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452418/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Schools: Property Transfer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 11 February 2016 to Question 25804, what the two sites are that are being considered for disposal within the Greater Manchester Combined Authority area.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","27178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452419","Department for Education","false","2016-02-23","<p>Schools in England fund free school meals out of the overall resources available to them. Since September 2014, all infant pupils in maintained schools in England have been entitled to free school meals, regardless of parental income. The government does provide specific funding to schools to pay for meals for infant pupils who are not eligible for benefits-related FSM. The breakdown of this funding is available at school level for financial year 2014-15 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-infant-free-school-meals-uifsm-provisional-funding-allocations-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-infant-free-school-meals-uifsm-provisional-funding-allocations-2014-to-2015</a>; and for financial year 2015-16 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-infant-free-school-meals-uifsm-funding-allocations-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-infant-free-school-meals-uifsm-funding-allocations-2015-to-2016</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-02-23T17:15:36.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452419/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452419/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-11","Free School Meals: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost has been of provision of free school meals by region in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","27163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452420","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-26","<p>It is important we have a vibrant, dynamic competitive energy market where energy companies work hard to attract customers though customer service as well as price. There are now 31 independent suppliers in the domestic retail energy market, up from 7 in 2010. Switching from a standard tariff to the best fixed, direct debit deal on the market, many people could save around £200 – and some could save more. During 2015, 3.8 million domestic customers switched electricity supplier and 2.8 million customers switched gas supplier.</p><p> </p><p>The Competition and Markets Authority are nearing the end of their enquiry into the energy markets. We are determined to do whatever it takes to ensure markets work well for consumers.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime, the Department will be working with Ofgem, the Ombudsman Service and Citizens Advice to make sure that the consumer complaints services are working for consumers and identifying systemic industry wide problems to improve customer service.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-26T14:00:11.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452420/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452420/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Energy: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Which? 2016 energy satisfaction survey, what steps she is taking to ensure the big six energy companies improve their customer service as well as reduce their prices.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","27094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452421","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-24","<p>More than £80m UK public sector support (including Ofgem innovation funding) has been committed to energy storage research, development and demonstration activities since 2012, which is helping to drive down the costs of storage and bring new technologies closer to market. The Department has provided more than £18m of innovation funding for development and demonstration storage technologies; including funding for four technology demonstration projects.</p><p> </p><p>We are facilitating the deployment of a smart grid through:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Rolling out smart meters which are an integral part of a smart grid;</li><li>The DECC-Ofgem Smart Grid Forum with a range of active workstreams to remove barriers to smart grid deployment.</li></ul>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-24T13:48:37.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452421/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452421/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Electricity: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what support her Department is providing for the development of (a) technologies for the improved storage of electricity and (b) locally-based smart grids.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","27081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452422","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility published updated Levy Control Framework (LCF) spend projections alongside the Spending Review on 25 November and we anticipate they will publish an update alongside the March budget. We will publish updated projections in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-24T13:49:08.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452422/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452422/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 22354, whether her Department plans to publish the updated detailed projections of the LCF overspend before the Easter recess.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","27058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452423","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-23","<p>We intend to reform the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) to improve value for money and reduce costs; improve cost control and budget management; and ensure the scheme focuses more on our long-term needs, while contributing to both our carbon and renewable energy targets. We plan to consult on the changes shortly. Therefore, I am unable to make specific commitments as to the future shape of the scheme at this point.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-23T15:10:10.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452423/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452423/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452423/answer/previousversion/46419","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has to support solar thermal systems in the domestic and non-domestic Renewable Heat Incentive.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","27051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452424","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-24","<p>Nugen is proposing to build three AP1000 reactors at Moorside in Cumbria. Nugen have indicated that Moorside would bring at least £10 billion of investment into the UK with estimated peak on-site employment of up to 6,000 during construction. During operation the reactors could sustain about 1,000 permanent jobs, with many more created through local and regional supply chains including in construction, manufacturing and engineering, although estimated numbers are not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding the Solway Firth Tidal Lagoon, the proposed project is in the early stages of development. It is too early to say how many jobs could be created.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-24T13:48:54.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452424/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452424/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452424/answer/previousversion/46417","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Energy: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many jobs are expected to be created in (a) the supply chain and (b) other areas as an indirect result of (i) new nuclear builds in Moorside and (ii) Solway Firth Tidal Lagoon project, West Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","27050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452425","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-22","<p>The climate change levy is collected on a national basis from energy suppliers and it is not possible to break down receipts by region. Detail on Climate Change Levy receipts on a national basis can be found at https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutyBulletins.aspx.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-22T16:50:33.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452425/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452425/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-11","Climate Change Levy: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much the climate change levy raised from non-domestic users in London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","26998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452426","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Government is currently in a bilateral negotiation with Tidal Lagoon Power Ltd regarding a possible Contract for Difference for their proposed project in Swansea Bay and there have been numerous meetings with the developer to discuss this project.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-22T16:46:46.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452426/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452426/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-11","Tidal Power: Solway Firth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many meetings her Department has had with representatives of Tidal Power Ltd on the proposed Solway Firth Tidal Lagoon project.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","27049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452427","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-23","<p>We have been working closely with the NFU and other industry bodies to identify major problems, not only in Copeland and Allerdale, but across Cumbria, Lancashire, Yorkshire and Durham where exceptional rainfall added to ground which was already saturated. In response, we have provided grants and other support to help farmers restore their land through the Farming Recovery Fund. Farmers affected by flooding will be able to claim grants of between £500 and £20,000 to cover the cost of restoring their farmland.</p><p> </p><p>In restoring damaged features such as bridges, fences or cross drains, we are encouraging farmers to protect against the future by considering building in protection against future flood damage. They can do this by locating these in a position where they are less likely to be damaged in the future or can be (for example, in the case of bridges) raised to reduce the risk of water damage. If farmers consider relocating features within their field, they could save replacement costs in the future.</p><p> </p><p>We have also put in place in Cumbria a new partnership, which includes representatives of agriculture businesses, to develop an action plan to be published this summer. The action plan will cover a range of issues, such as what improvements may be needed to flood defences in the region; upstream options for slowing key rivers to reduce peak water flows, and ways of building stronger links between local residents, businesses, community groups and flood defence planning.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-23T15:49:42.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452427/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452427/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Agriculture: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to ensure the resilience of agriculture businesses in (a) Copeland and (b) Allerdale to respond to the effects of (i) Storm Desmond and (ii) future severe weather events.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","27038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452428","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-23","<p>Flood Re is on target to start operating on 4 April. Flood Re will publish a list of participating insurers shortly before its launch.</p><p>For the first time it offers the prospect of available and affordable flood insurance to households at high flood risk.</p><p>The insurance market will continue to adapt after Flood Re is launched - it will be important for people to continue to shop around for the best deal.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-23T13:51:09.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452428/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452428/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the names of all insurers which have Flood Re-compatible products available to consumers on the day of launch of the Flood Re-scheme before that day.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","27046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452429","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Environmental Permitting (England and Wales) Regulations 2016 were laid before Parliament on 2 February. Subject to parliamentary approval, from April the Regulations will remove a number of low risk activities from the need for a flood defence consent permit from the Environment Agency, enabling it to focus on the highest risk activities. This includes allowing farmers to maintain ditches up to 1.5km long subject to a number of conditions.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-23T14:13:14.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452429/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452429/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Dredging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what powers she intends to extend to farmers in relation to the dredging of watercourses on their land.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","27063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452430","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-23","<p>Local Authorities (LAs) have powers to carry out flood risk management works, including maintenance on ordinary watercourses, while the Environment Agency (EA) has powers to carry out work on main rivers. In addition, under the Flood and Water Management Act 2010, flood risk management authorities may carry out work using the powers of other risk management authorities using public sector cooperation agreements. There are some excellent examples of LAs working in partnership with the EA and internal drainage boards, for example in Lincolnshire and Somerset.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-23T14:40:58.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452430/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452430/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to her comments at the Oxford Farming Conference on 6 January 2016 on additional powers to internal drainage boards, what plans she has to give local authorities a role in the maintenance of local watercourses.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","27067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452431","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Environment Agency allocates funding according to where it will have the most benefit to people and property using System Asset Management Plans for each of its flood defence asset systems. The Environment Agency discusses local maintenance programmes with local communities and groups like internal drainage boards. The Environment Agency publishes its maintenance programme online: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/river-and-coastal-maintenance-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/river-and-coastal-maintenance-programme</a>.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-23T16:08:24.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452431/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452431/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to her comments at the Oxford Farming conference on 6 January 2016 on decentralising decision-making, what steps she plans to take to ensure funding to tackle flooding and the maintenance of flood defences is allocated fairly and transparently to local groups.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","27066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452432","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-23","<p>Under the Welfare of Wild Animals in Travelling Circuses (England) Regulations 2012 there are currently two licences in force. One of these licences was suspended for twenty days in December 2015. Applications for renewals of both of these licences have been received and are currently being considered.</p><p>In May 2015, Defra also received an application for a licence from a further circus. As that circus subsequently decided not to tour in England in 2015 their application was discontinued without Defra making a decision whether to grant or refuse the application. In the last 12 months, no other applications for a licence have been received by Defra and no others have been refused, suspended or revoked.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-23T14:58:29.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452432/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452432/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Animal Welfare: Circuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many licenses issued under the Welfare of Wild Animals in Travelling Circuses (England) Regulations 2012 are currently in force; and how many applications for such licenses for what reasons have been (a) granted, (b) refused, (c) suspended and (d) revoked in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","27093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452433","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-22","<p>Repair and recovery grants were approved by the Executive Director of Operations on the advice of Environment Agency’s Large Project Review Group (LPRG) and its sub group LPRG Lite, which assessed the eligibility of schemes for recovery projects across the country.</p><p> </p><p>The approval for each recovery project undertaken by the Environment Agency followed a national procedure set out in an operational instruction which I have placed in the House Library.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally I have placed a copy of the Christchurch Beach Replenishment Scheme Asset Repair Planning Brief setting out the case for the work to take place under the recovery programme.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-22T13:32:05.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452433/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452433/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-11","Recycling: Christchurch","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 11 February 2016 to Question 26276, on recycling in Christchurch, if she will place in the Library a copy of the assessment including the cost-benefit analysis.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","27122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452434","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We remain deeply concerned about the human rights situation in the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea.</p><p>The British Government supports the principle that there must be no impunity for those accused of human rights violations and that crimes against humanity are appropriately investigated.</p><p>We will continue to work with members of the international community through multilateral fora, including the UN Security Council and the UN Human Rights Council, to ensure the regime is held to account for its appalling human rights record.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-22T15:23:13.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452434/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452434/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","North Korea: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking in cooperation with his international counterparts to pursue criminal responsibility of the leadership of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452435","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-26","I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 3 February 2016 (PQ 24568) regarding the UK Government’s concern about the erosion of judicial independence in the Maldives.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-26T14:09:36.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452435/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452435/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Maldives: Rule of Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the application of the rule of law in the Maldives.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452436","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The UK has contributed £330 million to support stability in Jordan since the start of the Syria crisis, £193 million of which has gone towards support for refugees and host communities. We are committed to continuing our support. On 4 February the UK co-hosted the ‘Supporting Syria and the Region 2016’ conference which secured over $11bn in pledges for Syria's neighbours from the international community, the largest sum raised for a cause on a single day. Jordan agreed a Compact at the conference which will see their receiving new funding, concessional finance, and support to increase investment in return for providing refugees with access to work and education. The UK will be at the forefront of work to deliver this plan.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:17:34.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452436/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452436/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Middle East: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to provide financial support to Jordan to tackle the humanitarian crisis in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452437","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>On 11 February, the Foreign Secretary took part in the latest round of the International Syria Support Group (ISSG) meeting in Munich. At that meeting ISSG foreign ministers discussed how to support the political process, including through confidence building measures and steps towards a ceasefire, as called for in UNSCR 2254.</p><p>The ISSG agreed the need to implement a cessation of hostilities within a week, to delivering humanitarian assistance to named besieged communities by the weekend of 13-14 February and to facilitate rapid progress in negotiations aimed at political transition. If implemented fully and properly by every ISSG member, this will be an important step towards relieving the killing and suffering in Syria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:09:52.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452437/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452437/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what diplomatic progress has been made by the international community in delivering peace in Syria.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452438","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>We use the strength of our relationship and engagement with Saudi Arabia to encourage reform. Saudi Arabia remains a Foreign and Commonwealth human rights priority country and we do not shy away from raising legitimate human rights concerns when it is appropriate to do so – I raised them most recently when I visited Riyadh last month. The Government of Saudi Arabia is well aware of our position on Human Rights issues.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:10:52.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452438/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452438/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Saudi Arabia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK's relationship with Saudi Arabia on human rights in that country.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452439","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence monitors incidents of alleged International Humanitarian Law (IHL) violations using available information which in turn informs our overall assessment of IHL compliance in Yemen. At this stage, looking at all the information available to us, we have not assessed that there has been a breach of IHL by the coalition, but continue to monitor the situation closely, seeking further information where appropriate. We regularly raise the importance of compliance with IHL to the Saudi Arabian government and other members of the military Coalition. Most recently I raised the issue of IHL compliance on 4 February with the Saudi Arabian Ambassador in London</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:14:02.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452439/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452439/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what evidence from independent bodies he has seen that Saudi Arabia is complying with international humanitarian law in the Yemen conflict.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452440","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The UK continues to play an active role in supporting the Libyan dialogue facilitated by the UN. The signing of the Libyan Political Agreement in Skhirat, Morocco on 17 December was a significant step forward. The Agreement sets out the process for establishment of a Government of National Accord (GNA). We continue to work with partners in the international community to encourage the Libyan parties to implement the Agreement in full.</p><p>The UK has been at the forefront of efforts to coordinate international support for the GNA. In October, we hosted a meeting with the UN and international donors and agencies to discuss plans for coordinated support from the international community to the GNA. This has been followed up through UN-hosted coordination meetings in Tunis. We stand ready to work with the international community to deliver a significant package of support to help a Government of National Accord to achieve a stable and prosperous future for all Libyan citizens. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), and I both spoke recently with Prime Minister designate Serraj and also with UN Special Representative Kobler to underline the UK’s continued support for the GNA process and UN efforts in this area.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-25T14:12:49.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452440/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452440/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Libya: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what diplomatic progress he has made in delivering a peaceful transition in Libya.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452441","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The situation is desperate for many communities within Syria and Iraq. We condemn in the strongest terms the atrocities committed by Daesh against Christians, Mandeans, Yezidis, and other minorities, as well as the majority Muslim population in Syria and Iraq who continue to bear the brunt of Daesh’s brutality.</p><p>It is a long-standing Government policy that any judgements on whether genocide has occurred are a matter for the international judicial system rather than governments or other non-judicial bodies. Our approach is to seek an end to all violations of International Humanitarian Law and to prevent their further escalation, irrespective of whether these violations fit the definition of specific international crimes.</p><p>Ultimately, the best way of preventing future atrocities is to defeat Daesh and its violent ideology. That’s why the UK is playing a leading role in a Global Coalition of more than 65 countries and international organisations to respond to Daesh’s inhumanity.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:16:05.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452441/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452441/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Syria: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether Daesh are committing genocide in Syria.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452442","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>Yes. The UK was a prime-mover for the creation of the Arms Trade Treaty (ATT) and continues to be an active advocate of a robust Treaty. The UK was amongst the first to sign the ATT in 2013 and ratified on 2 April 2014. We believe that the ATT will be stronger for every State which accedes to or ratifies it.</p><p>Universalisation will remain a key priority. The UK played an important role in the preparatory discussions leading to the First Conference of States Parties, and was a Vice-President of that Conference, brokering agreement on key decisions to establish sustainable mechanisms for the future viability of the ATT.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-22T14:17:41.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452442/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452442/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Arms Trade: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he supports the aims of the Arms Trade Treaty.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452443","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 27 January (question 23192) to the hon. Member for Chesterfield (Toby Perkins).","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-24T16:12:18.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452443/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452443/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support the global abolition of the death penalty.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452444","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","The UK continues to work closely with the Turkish government, including through implementation of the EU-Turkey Action Plan, to ensure that refugees continue to receive support and protection. We welcome Turkey’s generosity in hosting more than 2.5 million Syrian refugees in Turkey, and the ongoing support it is providing bilaterally to refugees amassing at its border with Syria. On 4 February 2016, the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) announced that the UK will more than double our total pledge to the Syria crisis from £1.12 billion to over £2.3 billion. This is the UK's largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-24T16:14:21.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452444/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452444/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what diplomatic steps he is taking to tackle the refugee crisis on the Turkish-Syrian border.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452445","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We are aware of the tragic death of Mr Regini, an Italian national, following his disappearance on 25 January and pass our condolences to his friends and family at this difficult time. We support Italian and Egyptian efforts to investigate the circumstances of the tragic death of Mr Regeni, and are in contact with the Italian and Egyptian authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-22T15:27:04.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452445/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452445/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Giulio Regeni","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 11 February 2016 to Question 26339, what representations he is making to the Egyptian government on an independent inquiry being carried out into the death of Giulio Regeni.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","27188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452446","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-26","We are aware of the cases of the US and Canadian nationals who have been arrested and detained by the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK). Sweden, which has consular responsibility for these individuals, is providing assistance.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-26T14:13:35.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452446/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452446/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","North Korea: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of North Korea on the arrest of Mr Otto Frederick Warmbier, and the detention of Hyeon Soo Lim and Kim Dong Chul.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452447","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>A more stable, secure and prosperous Moldova is important for the stability of the European neighbourhood. The situation in Moldova was discussed by EU Foreign Ministers on 15 February.</p><p>The EU Foreign Affairs Council concluded that the the current difficulties can be solved only via constructive dialogue among all political forces in the country, which takes into account the expectations of the people of the Republic of Moldova, and that tangible results on reforms are needed to restore trust.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-25T16:17:52.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452447/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452447/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Moldova: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the political situation in Moldova on stability and security in that region.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","27109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452448","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We continue to have serious concerns about Iran’s support for Hamas and the military wing of Hezbollah, which reportedly includes the provision of financial resources and training as well as the supply of military equipment. We call on Iran to end such support, which directly undermines the prospects for lasting peace in the region, and to abide by all relevant UN obligations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-22T15:26:12.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452448/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452448/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Iran: Hezbollah and Hamas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the extent of funding from Iran for (a) Hezbollah and (b) Hamas; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","27183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452449","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>We take freedom of religion or belief extremely seriously. We regularly urge Governments to protect the right of all individuals to practise their religion or belief free from persecution or discrimination. In this regard, we are concerned with the plight of the Ahmadiyah community in Bangka regency. Our Ambassador in Jakarta has discussed these issues, including the plight of the Ahamdiyah community, with the Minister of Religious Affairs, Indonesian civil society, and religious leaders. He urged them to ensure the rights of all individuals to practise their religion or belief freely were fully respected and protected.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-26T14:24:39.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452449/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452449/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Indonesia: Ahmadiyya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions the Government has had with the Indonesian government on the situation of Ahmadis in Bangka, Indonesia.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452450","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>We condemn the glorification of terrorism and all incitement to commit violence, whichever side it comes from. Our posts in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem supply regular updates on the current situation in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. Included in these updates are reports on incidents of incitement from both the Palestinian Authority and the Israeli authorities.</p><p>We have also received representations from members of the public regarding reports of incitement by the Palestinian Authority.</p><p>We continue to support Palestinian calls to reinstate the Tripartite Committee as the appropriate channel to deal with allegations of Palestinian or Israeli incitement.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:02:32.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452450/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452450/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Palestinians: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25988, on Palestinian radicalism, what recent reports he has received on incitement to commit violence by the Palestinian Authority.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","27191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452451","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>The UK, through FCO and DFID is encouraging the government of Bangladesh to improve working conditions and safety standards in the garment sector in a number of ways.</p><p>The UK actively lobbies the government on these issues through the 3 + 5 mechanism that was established as part of the Sustainability Compact.</p><p>We are also working with the Government of Bangladesh to improve the framework within which factories operate. As part of our Garments sector programme, we are building the capacity of the government to significantly improve factory regulation and inspection by strengthening the Department for Inspection of Factories and Establishment. Through our support, this Department will have a 575 member cadre of professional labour inspectors, who among other things, will ensure that factories are safe and that they pay workers their salaries and overtime payments according to the law. The UK has also helped fund building, fire and electrical safety inspections in 1500 garment factories.</p><p>In 2013, as a result of lobbying from major stakeholders including the UK, Bangladesh raised the minimum wage for the country’s garment workers by 77 percent to 5,300 taka (£42) per month.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-25T13:44:22.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452451/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452451/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Bangladesh: Factories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to encourage the government of Bangladesh to improve (a) working conditions, (b) safety standards and (c) pay in clothes factories used by international companies in Bangladesh.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452452","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We supply funding for projects delivered by the following 10 Israeli Non-Government Offices (NGOs) through the Conflict Stability and Security Fund: The Peres Centre for Peace; Injaz - Centre for Professional Arab Local Governance; Kids Creating Peace; Yesh Din; Gisha; Peace Now; Terrestrial Jerusalem; The International Peace and Cooperation Centre; Rabbis for Human Rights and the Jerusalem Community Advocacy Network.</p><p>We also fund projects delivered by the following NGOs through the Bilateral Programme Budget: Burj Al Luqluq Youth Center and Silwan Youth Center.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-22T15:38:51.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452452/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452452/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Middle East: Conflict Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25979, which 10 Israeli NGOs receive funding from the Conflict Stability and Security Fund; and which two NGOs receive funds through the Bilateral Programme Budgets.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","27124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452453","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The European Commission said on 2 December 2015 that the conditions for starting a Rule of Law framework procedure against Hungary had not been fulfilled. The UK Government expects all member states of the EU to respect human rights, including freedom of speech and of the media, and to respect the rule of law.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-25T16:18:12.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452453/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452453/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Hungary: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will discuss with his EU counterparts the EU undertaking a rule of law procedure against Hungary; and what representations he is making to his counterparts on recent reforms by the Hungarian government.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","27146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452454","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>Secondary legislation required for the referendum is making good progress. The Conduct Regulations, which set out the detailed framework of how the poll will be administered, have been debated in both Houses of Parliament. The date of the referendum must be agreed by Parliament in another statutory instrument which was laid before Parliament in draft on 22 February.</p><p>On 23 February the Electoral Commission published its &quot;assessment of readiness&quot; which endorsed the Government's approach and noted that &quot;arrangements for delivery of a well-run referendum on the UK's membership of the European Union are well advanced&quot;.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-26T14:41:11.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452454/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452454/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on preparations for the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","27161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452455","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We work closely with international partners to exert pressure on the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) regarding its human rights track record both through multilateral fora, including the UN Security Council and the UN Human Rights Council, as well as through our critical engagement with the regime both in Pyongyang and London.</p><p>We are aware of the appalling human rights situation in the DPRK as described by the UN Special Rapporteur as well as set out in the UN Commission of Inquiry report. Our policy priorities continue to be the improvement of the human rights situation for the North Korean people and an end to the DPRK’s nuclear and ballistic missile programme.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-22T15:30:20.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452455/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452455/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","North Korea: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the comment made on 22 January 2016 by the UN Special Rapporteur on the situation of human rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452456","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The UK has strongly supported the work of the UN Commission of Inquiry on Human Rights in the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK), and we remain deeply concerned about the human rights situation in the DPRK that the report outlined. We have urged DPRK authorities to respond in detail to the contents of the report and to address the human rights violations that it documents. We also maintain pressure on the DPRK on human rights through multilateral fora, including the UN Security Council and the UN Human Rights Council, and through our critical engagement with the regime both in Pyongyang and London.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-22T15:43:39.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452456/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452456/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","North Korea: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the implications for its policies of the recommendations of the UN Commission of Inquiry on human rights in North Korea, published in February 2014.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452457","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>I share My Right Honourable Friend’s concerns about the devastating impact of land seizures in Zimbabwe. The British Embassy in Harare frequently raises land security – and the importance of upholding the rule of law – with the Government of Zimbabwe. Most recently, they highlighted the British Government’s serious concerns that the seizure of the land of Zimbabwean farmer, Mr Philip Rankin, did not follow the provisions of the Zimbabwean constitution. The British Government has always said that it would support a fair, transparent and pro-poor land reform programme in Zimbabwe. This is vital if Zimbabwe is to realise its great economic and social potential.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-02-22T14:32:18.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452457/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452457/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Zimbabwe: Farmers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if the Government will provide assistance to farmers in Zimbabwe who are forced from their land by the policies of the government of that country.","false","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","27043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452458","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>No Foreign Office Minister is planning to attend this meeting. We understand that a Home Office Minister is considering attendance and will make a decision in the coming weeks.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-24T14:08:25.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452458/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452458/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether a Minister from his Department plans to attend the high-level meeting on global responsibility sharing through pathways for admission of Syrian refugees hosted by UNHRC in Geneva on 30 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","27045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452459","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>There is clearly support in some governments within the European Union for further political integration, but there are other, more sceptical voices, too. The recital in paragraph one of section C makes clear that “the United Kingdom, in the light of the specific situation it has under the Treaties, is not committed to further political integration into the European Union”.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-23T16:06:47.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452459/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452459/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452459/answer/previousversion/46421","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the recital in paragraph one of section C of the revised version of the draft EU decision on a new settlement for the UK, what assessment he has made of whether the objectives of political integration enjoys wide support in the union.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","27033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452460","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>I responded to the Rt. hon. Member’s letter on 14 January.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-25T13:47:15.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452460/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452460/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when she intends to answer the letter to her dated 4 January 2016 with regard to Ms J. Ellis.","false","Biography information for Sir Gerald Kaufman","Manchester, Gorton","Sir Gerald Kaufman","26983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452461","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>Since the General Election, we have adopted a new strategic approach to human rights, refocusing our work around three themes: democratic values and the rule of law; strengthening the rules-based international system; and human rights for a stable world. Our work on freedom of religion or belief is an integral part of each of these themes.</p><p>The Advisory Group on Freedom of Religion or Belief, as with our other former thematic human rights advisory groups, provided important contributions to our policy and activities. Under our new approach, our thematic advisory groups remain part of the expert constituency to which we turn when designing and delivering human rights initiatives. For example, we involved members of the former Advisory Group on Freedom of Religion or Belief in a workshop on Christians in the Middle East that we held in November 2015. We put forward another expert to form part of the Independent Review Panel of the Global Community Engagement and Resilience Fund. We continue to convene regular meetings of the Foreign Secretary's Advisory Group on Human Rights to discuss a range of topics of interest to its members.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-23T17:54:29.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452461/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452461/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452461/answer/previousversion/46719","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, for what reasons the Advisory Group on Freedom of Religion and Belief was not re-established after the 2015 General Election; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","26993"
