"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452486","Home Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The average hourly pay for Civil Servants in the Home Office by gender and part and full time workers, for each of the last five years is in Table 1.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-24T16:25:42.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452486/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452486/answer","Table 1 PQ 27001.xlsx","Table 1 PQ 27001.xlsx","Average hourly earnings of employees","Average hourly earnings of employees","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452486/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Home Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of her Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452487","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We know that the majority of forces in England and Wales use Body Worn Video (BWV) to some extent.</p><p>However the deployment of BWV is an operational decision for chief officers and the Home Office does not hold information on how many officers are equipped with BWV</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-22T17:17:07.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452487/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452487/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers wear body-worn cameras in (a) Northamptonshire and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","27034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452488","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) offers an Update Service which can deliver savings in both time and costs. With the certificate holder’s permission, a potential employer or another person with a legitimate interest can check via a DBS online portal whether any new information has been recorded since the certificate was issued. Only if there has been a change is there any need for the individual to obtain a new certificate. This enables portability of certificates between organisations. It is only applicable where the certificate holder is moving within the same workforce – such as work with children or work with vulnerable adults. Where the person is moving between workforces a new certificate will be required, as there may be different factors affecting decisions about whether information is appropriate for disclosure.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-22T14:56:29.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452488/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452488/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of making Disclosure and Barring Service certificates portable and valid from organisation to organisation by the person concerned.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","26982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452489","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-22","<p>HMRC actively engages with developing countries and has recently agreed treaties with Senegal and Zambia. Tax treaties encourage the appropriate tax treatment of cross-border economic activity, promote international trade and investment and ultimately lead to sustainable tax revenues.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-22T13:27:32.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452489/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452489/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Developing Countries: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made an assessment of the effects on the tax revenue of developing countries of tax treaties with the UK.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","26991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452490","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-22","<p>The UK is one of the leading donors on tax and development and we have committed to double our support on tax by 2020 as part of the Addis Tax Initiative. DFID is currently engaged in, or developing, tax reform in 26 of our 28 priority countries. This includes support from the Tax Capacity Building Unit in HMRC we established in 2013 and from international organisations such as OECD, the Global Forum and the World Bank which DFID funds to provide technical assistance to tackle tax evasion and multinational tax avoidance.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-22T13:27:59.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452490/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452490/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Developing Countries: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department provides to developing countries to improve their tax revenue gathering capabilities.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","26992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452491","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>The figures given in the table below represent the average (mean) salary for each of the defined categories requested as at the 31<sup>st</sup> of January in each of the last three years. Providing information for 2012 and 2013 could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year <br> (as at 31/01)</p></td><td><p>Average Female Hourly Rate <br> (£)</p></td><td><p>Average Male Hourly Rate <br> (£)</p></td><td><p>Average Full Time Hourly Rate <br> (£)</p></td><td><p>Average Part Time Hourly Rate <br> (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>24.95</p></td><td><p>26.53</p></td><td><p>25.76</p></td><td><p>25.05</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>24.95</p></td><td><p>27.03</p></td><td><p>25.79</p></td><td><p>27.10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>25.15</p></td><td><p>27.18</p></td><td><p>26.08</p></td><td><p>25.68</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>DFID pay is set within Civil Service rules defined by HM Treasury, and grade specific scales operate regardless of gender. Differences in hourly rates apply due to the grade and location profile of the organisation.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-25T16:11:01.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452491/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452491/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Department for International Development: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of her Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452492","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-22","<p>The DFID Palestinian Programme supports the HMG objective of protecting the viability of a two state solution. DFID’s work in the Occupied Palestinian Territories tends to consist of large-scale and strategic programmes that fit within our three priority areas; state building, economic development and alleviating poverty and vulnerability. Through the cross-government Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF), the UK continues to support several projects which promote coexistence. These projects include support for the Peres Centre for Peace Training Doctors Programme which brings Israelis and Palestinians together through medical care and training to combat stereotypes and build trust. Additionally we work on projects with youth groups and through sport to encourage engagement between Israelis and Palestinians.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","27126","2016-02-22T13:28:54.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452492/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452492/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 26100, what proportion of her Department's financial assistance for Palestinian development funds other projects which foster coexistence between Israelis and Palestinians.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","27125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452493","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-22","<p>The DFID Palestinian Programme supports the HMG objective of protecting the viability of a two state solution. DFID’s work in the Occupied Palestinian Territories tends to consist of large-scale and strategic programmes that fit within our three priority areas; state building, economic development and alleviating poverty and vulnerability. Through the cross-government Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF), the UK continues to support several projects which promote coexistence. These projects include support for the Peres Centre for Peace Training Doctors Programme which brings Israelis and Palestinians together through medical care and training to combat stereotypes and build trust. Additionally we work on projects with youth groups and through sport to encourage engagement between Israelis and Palestinians.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","27125","2016-02-22T13:28:54.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452493/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452493/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 26100, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of the £349 million spent in support of Palestinian development from 2011 to 2015 which has gone to support projects which promote coexistence.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","27126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452494","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-22","<p>We are awaiting confirmation from OCHA and the EU on the details of the structures demolished in South Hebron. We have raised our concerns with the Israeli government over the demolition of these structures in South Hebron. Demolitions of Palestinian homes and buildings cause unnecessary suffering to ordinary Palestinians, and are harmful to the peace process. The UK continues to raise with Israeli authorities our serious concern at the increase in demolitions of Palestinian properties and structures in Area C of the West Bank and in East Jerusalem.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-22T13:30:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452494/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452494/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Israel: 
Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 25684, what discussions she has had with her EU counterparts on the (a) destruction of structures confirmed to have been funded by the EU and (b) possibility of seeking costs related to that damage from Israeli authorities.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452495","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-22","<p><em> </em></p><p>The Accord has played an important role in pushing up working conditions and safety standards in the Garments sector in Bangladesh. Since 2013 the Accord has independently inspected 1, 390 factories in the supply chains of their signatory brands. It has then supported those factories that continue to sell to Accord brands to implement Corrective Action Plans, resulting in safer factories for 2.4 million workers.</p><p> </p><p>A review of the Bangladesh Sustainability Compact, completed by the EU, US and ILO in January 2016, recognised the contribution of private sector initiatives such as the Accord in improving labour, health and safety conditions for Bangladeshi workers.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-22T13:30:53.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452495/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452495/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-11","Bangladesh: Working Conditions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of the Accord on Fire and Building Safety on working conditions and safety standards in Bangladesh.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452496","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-22","<p>Opinion 2/13 of The European Court of Justice raises a number of complex issues which have fundamental implications for any proposed agreement for the EU to accede to the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). It will be very difficult for the EU and contracting parties to the ECHR to work out where this leaves the accession process and to negotiate a revised accession agreement on that basis. There is clearly no prospect of accession being achieved any time soon. In any discussions we will continue to make our ongoing concerns clear.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-22T16:27:17.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452496/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452496/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 23 July 2015 to Question 6280, what work has been carried out to mitigate the risks identified from the EU's accession to the European Court of Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","27179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452497","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>The family court takes the issue of domestic violence extremely seriously. Where domestic violence or abuse is admitted or proven, any child arrangements order put in place must protect the safety and wellbeing of the child and the parent with whom the child is living, and not expose them to the risk of further harm. In particular, the court must be satisfied that any contact ordered with a parent who has perpetrated violence or abuse is safe and in the best interests of the child.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Where the court concludes that direct contact is safe and beneficial for the child, it can impose conditions such as supervised contact to protect the child.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice has improved funding for support and advice projects led by advice, voluntary and the pro bono sector to assist litigants in person and provide them with the information and skills to effectively represent themselves in court. Further, a person who has evidence of domestic violence or abuse, or the risk of such violence or abuse, can still obtain legal aid for advice and legal representation in the family court for a protective order or to deal with other family matters, such as a child arrangements order. This is to make sure that actual or potential victims of domestic violence or abuse are given the protection they need to keep them and other family members, including children, safe.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-03-01T10:22:30.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452497/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452497/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 1.26 of the National Audit Office report, Implementing reforms to civil legal aid reports, published in November 2014, what assessment he has made of the effect of the increase in the number of litigants in person in family courts for cases involving contact with children on the quality of child arrangements orders made in families known to have a history of domestic abuse.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","27192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452498","Attorney General","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) identifies the type of crime prosecuted with reference to twelve principal offence categories. The Principal Offence Category is assigned at the end of a prosecution case to indicate the most serious offence with which the defendant is charged at the time of finalisation. It is not possible to disaggregate the number of prosecutions for individual offences recorded in each category or the times involved on specific categories without incurring a disproportionate cost.</p><p>The attached tables contain details of the number of completed prosecutions in magistrates’ courts and at the Crown Court, for each principal offence category, in each of the last ten years.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-22T16:32:30.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452498/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452498/answer","CPS prosecutions in magistrates courts and at the Crown Court.docx","CPS prosecutions in magistrates courts and at the Crown Court.docx","CPS prosecution tables","CPS prosecution tables","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452498/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-11","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many cases relating to each type of crime were prosecuted by the CPS in (a) magistrates' courts and (b) the Crown Court in each of the last 10 years; how many hours the CPS spent on prosecutions of each type in each type of court in those years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","27182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452499","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-25T17:42:54.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452499/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452499/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of his Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452500","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>Every family court has a system to support vulnerable court users. Protective measures are put in place whenever this is considered to be appropriate. These can include separate waiting areas, additional security and the use of separate entrances where appropriate. Parties can also request special measures such as the use of protective screens in the hearing or the use of a video link.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-03-01T09:58:31.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452500/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452500/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many family courts have special access measures in place for victims of domestic violence attending the court for child contact cases.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","27056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452501","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>Judicial training is a matter for the judiciary and is fulfilled by the Judicial College, which reports to the Lord Chief Justice and Senior President of Tribunals. Some outside organisations have been invited to provide input, under judicial direction, into judicial training programmes and materials, including on specialist subjects. The Judicial College does not have a consolidated record of which organisations these are.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Judicial College Strategy, training in social context issues is incorporated into all training programmes and diversity and equal treatment issues are woven into the case studies used in training. The strategy is publicly available <a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/about-the-judiciary/training-support/judicial-college/judicial-college-strategy-2015-2017/" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/about-the-judiciary/training-support/judicial-college/judicial-college-strategy-2015-2017/</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-25T13:06:57.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452501/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452501/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","Judges: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which organisations have provided diversity and equality training to judges since 1 January 2012.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","27062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452502","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-26","<p>Equality and diversity training is accessed through the Civil Service Learning (CSL) suite of products. All Prison Governors have access to this learning offer.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to the availability of CSL, up until 31 March 2013 NOMS ran an in-house package for equality training that tackled inappropriate behaviour called ‘Challenge it, Change it’. This was available to all staff including Prison Governors.</p><p> </p><p>Equality and diversity consideration is a component of all business specific learning.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-26T14:12:15.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452502/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452502/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","Prison Governors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which organisations have provided diversity and equality training to prison governors since 1 January 2012.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","27060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452503","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Legal Aid Agency publishes this information as part of its official statistics, the most recent edition of which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/legal-aid-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/legal-aid-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015</a>.</p><p>Statistics covering the final quarter of 2015 will be published in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-23T17:09:05.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452503/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452503/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-11","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for Exceptional Case Funding there were in 2015; and how many of those applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","27061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452504","Leader of the House","false","2016-02-26","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him by my right hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office on 26 February 2016, to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-02-10/26973/" target="_blank">26973</a>.</p><p> </p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-02-26T14:37:04.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452504/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452504/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-02-11","Cabinet Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of his Office were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452505","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>This information is not held and to provide it would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-02-22T13:07:56.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452505/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452505/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-11","Northern Ireland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of her Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452506","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>In October 2012, I informed the families that I agreed with my predecessor’s decision not to hold a public inquiry into the events in Ballymurphy. I explained this position when I met the families in January 2013. I considered the families’ more recent request for an independent review panel carefully. On 29 April 2014, I advised the families of my decision against instigating an independent review panel. I do not believe the balance of public interest lies in establishing an inquiry or independent review into the deaths in Ballymurphy in August 1971. I do not believe that such a review would provide answers which are not already in the public domain or covered by existing legal processes such as the inquests.</p><p> </p><p>I continue to receive representations from members of the public, politicians and others seeking further investigation into the events in Ballymurphy and into various other events that occurred during the troubles.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-02-22T12:55:51.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452506/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452506/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-11","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent representations she has had on a public inquiry into events in Ballymurphy in August 1971; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","27166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452507","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>I have discussed the importance of air connectivity between Northern Ireland and London and the work of the Airports Commission with Ministers in the Government, the Northern Ireland Executive and airport operators.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","27170","2016-02-22T13:18:47.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452507/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452507/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-11","Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what representations she has received on the effect on Northern Ireland of proposals for new runway capacity in the London area.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","27171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452508","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>I have discussed the importance of air connectivity between Northern Ireland and London and the work of the Airports Commission with Ministers in the Government, the Northern Ireland Executive and airport operators.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","27171","2016-02-22T13:18:47.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452508/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452508/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-11","Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with (a) the Northern Ireland Executive and (b) airport operators in Northern Ireland and Great Britain on the Airports Commission: Final Report, published in July 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","27170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452509","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>The inclusion of investment protections and investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) provisions in the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) should not affect how public services are provided in Scotland or the rest of the UK. Investment protection seeks to protect businesses and individuals who have made investments overseas from unfair or discriminatory treatment and ISDS is about providing an independent legal means to resolve disputes which have arisen under the treaty. The proposals cannot force governments to open markets or privatise public services.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has bilateral investment agreements with over 90 countries which contain ISDS provisions and there has never been a successful claim brought against the UK.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-02T17:50:35.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452509/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452509/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Prime Minister has made of the potential effect of the investor state dispute settlement clause of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership on public services managed by the Scottish government.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","27195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452510","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-23","<p>We expect that the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) will be a “mixed” agreement, covering areas of both EU and Member State competence. In that case, it will be subject to agreement by each EU Member State, the EU Council and the European Parliament. As part of this process the agreement will be subject to Parliamentary scrutiny before it is ratified by the UK.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-23T15:48:01.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452510/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452510/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-11","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership is a mixed-competence agreement that will require ratification by the national parliaments of all EU member states.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","27143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452511","Scotland Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>The UK Government does not intend to devolve responsibility for the North Sea oil industry.</p><p>The Smith Commission Agreement, agreed by all of Scotland’s main parties, was clear on the powers that would be devolved to the Scottish Parliament and Scottish Ministers, and the Scotland Bill, currently before Parliament, delivers these powers in full.</p><p>The Smith Commission agreed that all aspects of the taxation of oil and gas receipts and the licensing of offshore oil and gas extraction would remain reserved.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-02-26T13:07:59.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452511/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452511/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-02-11","North Sea Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if the Prime Minister will make it his policy to devolve responsibilities for the North Sea oil industry to the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","27144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452512","Department of Health","false","2016-02-22","<p>Yes. The Secretary of State’s speech of 11 January does include these provisions, as new investment will apply to all age groups.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-22T12:30:34.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452512/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452512/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-11","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the reference in the Prime Minister's speech on life chances of 11 January 2016 to health liaison psychiatry services in A&E departments includes provision for paediatric mental health liaison psychiatry services in A&E departments.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27187"
