ivity for a city centre High Speed 2 station at Victoria which Network Rail was involved in.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","27132 ; 27133 ; 27134 ; 27137 ; 27138 ; 27140","2016-02-25T12:24:08.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452528/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452528/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of additional jobs and (b) amount of additional housing resulting from a Victoria High Speed 2 station location.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452529","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>Analysis of the Sheffield City Region station options was published in the ‘Engineering options report; West Midlands to Leeds’ dated March 2012. This included analysis of several station sites around the city centre.</p><p> </p><p>The current estimated difference in cost between locating a High Speed station at Victoria and Meadowhall is £680m. Previous work on the cost of options at Victoria and other city centre sites are not comparable to the current estimate given above. With regards to the Meadowhall station, following the 2013 public consultation, no significant changes have been made to the original station design therefore there have not been any changes in cost.</p><p> </p><p>When recommending a station location HS2 Ltd. uses a number of criteria, including;</p><p> </p><ol><li>engineering and construction feasibility;</li><li>sustainability;</li><li>demand considerations, including journey times;</li><li>cost; and</li><li>wider impacts</li></ol><p> </p><p>Potential options were sifted by HS2 Ltd. according to these criteria. To support and challenge this approach, external stakeholders and advisors from the Department’s Project Representative Team were involved in reviewing the process and outcomes where appropriate. Further information about the appraisal process can be found in the 2012 ‘Options for phase two of the high speed rail network’ report and 2013 ‘Appraisal of Sustainability’ report. Both of these documents are available on the government website.</p><p> </p><p>Analysis undertaken by HS2 shows that the introduction of the Sheffield Meadowhall HS2 station could support up to 5,400 jobs and up to 300 residential units, while a HS2 station at Victoria could support an estimated 9,000 jobs and 900 housing units.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, I can confirm that Department for Transport officials have received a copy of Sheffield City Region's study into connectivity for a city centre High Speed 2 station at Victoria which Network Rail was involved in.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","27132 ; 27133 ; 27134 ; 27137 ; 27138 ; 27139","2016-02-25T12:24:08.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452529/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452529/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what methodology his Department used to determine that the proposed Sheffield station should be at Meadowhall and not Victoria; and whether that methodology has been independently verified.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452530","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>There is an initial budget of £650k for the Emissions Testing Programme. To retain independence we are not seeking contributions from manufacturers. Where testing is being done specifically on Skoda vehicles outside of this test programme, Skoda will be charged on a case by case basis by the Vehicle Certification Agency (VCA). The fees are set out in The Motor Vehicles (Type Approval and Approval Marks)(Fees) Regulations 1999, as amended. VCA will charge between £8,000 and £10,000 per vehicle. The emissions test facilities will be charged separately.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-22T14:47:49.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452530/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452530/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25018, what his Department's estimate is of the cost of the Emissions Testing Programme; and what Skoda's financial contribution is to the ongoing testing of VW vehicles outside that programme.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","27119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452531","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Office for Rail and Road (ORR), as Highways Monitor, published a six month report on Highways England’s performance in December 2015. This comments on the Highways England Biodiversity Action Plan, which was published in June 2015.</p><p> </p><p>ORR will report annually on Highways England’s performance and in line with the requirement in the Licence, I expect Highways England to publish their environmental strategy shortly.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-22T14:40:10.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452531/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452531/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Highways England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of Highways England's compliance with the conditions on environmental duties set out in paragraphs 5.23 and 5.24 of the Highways England: Licence, published in April 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","27117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452532","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>Data on all annual season ticket issues and the revenue associated with them was used to create an implied average annual season ticket fare. This was then uprated under both the RPI+0 policy, and the Department’s previous assumption about future policy (RPI+1), using the OBR’s assumptions of future RPI increases. The difference between the two was then summed to reach an average saving of £425 over the period.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-22T14:52:45.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452532/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452532/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's press release of 18 August 2015, entitled Earnings outstrip rail fare increases for the first time in a decade, what the statistical evidential basis is for the statement that increasing regulated rail fares by the retail price index between 2016 and 2020 will save season-ticket holders around £425 each.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","27121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452533","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Department had a Cycle Stakeholder Forum, established from 2011 – 2014, which had some sub-groups including a group on cycle health, chaired by the Department of Health. The sub-group was disbanded when the Cycle Stakeholder Forum was dissolved.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-22T14:27:23.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452533/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452533/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25993, whether his Department had a Cycling Health sub-group.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","27118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452534","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>Highways England has committed to provide a safer, integrated and more accessible strategic road network for cyclists, walkers and other vulnerable road users. Through the first Road Investment Strategy for Highways England, a ring-fenced allocation of £175 million has been made available between 2015 and 2020 to improve the safety of the Strategic Road Network and improve conditions for cyclists and other vulnerable road users.</p><p> </p><p>The Highways England current delivery plan states that £78 million will be used to improve conditions for those cycling alongside and crossing the Strategic Road Network. The remaining £97 million will be used to enhance the safety of our network, with £20 million of this specifically targeted at improving facilities to provide a more accessible and integrated network.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-22T14:56:12.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452534/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452534/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to performance indicators for helping cyclists, walkers and other vulnerable users of the network in the Highways England operational metrics manual, whether any additional resource funding has been allocated under the Road Investment Strategy to reduce vulnerable user casualties.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","27180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452535","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Travelcard map, showing the zone in which each station falls, is set out as part of the Travelcard Agreement between the Train Operating Companies and Transport for London (TfL). Any changes to station zones must be proposed by a signatory to the Agreement and then agreed by the remaining signatories. The government is not a signatory to the Agreement and therefore has no role in proposing such changes to station zones.</p><p> </p><p>Once a change is proposed by TfL and the Train Operating Companies, the Department for Transport can approve or reject the change proposals. This decision is made by the Secretary of State for Transport, on the basis of a business case and other wider policy and initiatives that may be considered at the time. If the proposal does not represent good value for money, it would be unlikely to get approval. It would be inappropriate for the Government to promote or back any proposals outside of this established process.</p><p> </p><p>In the current rail franchising contracts there are commitments for train operators to bring forward proposals to extend Oyster and Contactless to Swanley, Epsom, Hertford North, Luton Airport Parkway and Welwyn Garden City. The Secretary of State will consider these proposals on their individual merits when they have been developed and submitted in accordance with the process set out above.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-25T15:10:50.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452535/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452535/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Public Transport: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether it is his policy to expand London's transport zones to include (a) Spelthorne constituency and (b) other new areas inside the M25 orbital that do not use the oyster system.","false","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","27194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452536","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Severn River Crossing concession is currently forecast to end in 2018.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-22T13:57:47.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452536/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452536/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he estimates the Severn River crossing concession will end.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","27127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452537","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>Departmental Ministers and officials have held meetings with the Senior Traffic Commissioner and with the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency since 2010, but the precise number is not calculable.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-25T16:12:30.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452537/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452537/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-11","Department for Transport: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2016 to Question 23952, how many meetings Ministers and officials of his Department have had with the Senior Traffic Commissioner and the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","27149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452538","Wales Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Wales Office is subject to Ministry of Justice (MoJ) policies for HR and pay purposes.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-02-25T12:53:23.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452538/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452538/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-02-11","Wales Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of his Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452539","Women and Equalities","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Government Equalities Office (GEO) transferred into the Department for Education on 1 September 2015. Prior to September, GEO were part of DCMS. We are therefore not able to provide historical salary data.</p><p>The Government Equalities Office (GEO) pays annual salaries. These have been converted to hourly rates using the calculation ((Gross Basic Salary*FTE)/52)/Weekly hours.</p><p>Please find details of the average hourly earnings of the groups of GEO staff requested below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Mar-11</p></td><td><p>Mar-12</p></td><td><p>Mar-13</p></td><td><p>Mar-14</p></td><td><p>Mar-15</p></td><td><p>Jan-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>£25.33</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>£23.38</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full-time</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>£24.06</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Part-time</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>£23.94</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-02-26T14:47:19.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452539/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452539/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-02-11","Government Equalities Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of the Government Equalities Office were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","26999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452540","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-22","<p>The detailed policy design is still under development. We will set out our policy design for the Youth Obligation in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We will be conducting a stakeholder engagement exercise with organisations and employers shortly.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-22T11:51:14.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452540/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452540/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Unemployment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress his Department has made on developing proposals for implementing the Youth Obligation; and what organisations his Department are consulting to inform that process.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","26997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452541","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions pays employees an annual salary rather than an hourly rate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department uses a grade structure to determine salary rates. The grade structure is underpinned by Job Evaluation and Grading Support (JEGS), an analytical job evaluation tool which meets all requirements of legislation and EHRC (Equality and Human Rights Commission) statutory codes of practice on Equal Pay. The use of JEGS and its application in determining the appropriate grade for a role enables us to determine where employees are doing equal work based on “work rated as equivalent”.</p><p> </p><p>DWP Equality data is published on an annual basis on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-work-pensions/about/equality-and-diversity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-work-pensions/about/equality-and-diversity</a> .This includes the average male and female pay for each year.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the gender pay gap in DWP was 3.7%. ONS reported that the mean gender pay gap within the UK was 19.2%, indicating that the gender pay gap within the DWP is considerably narrower than the UK gender pay gap.</p><p> </p><p>Part time employees receive a ‘pro-rated’ salary based on their working hours. Below, we have provided average salaries for part time employees based on the Full Time Equivalent (FTE) salary rate.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2015 Average FTE Salary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full time</p></td><td><p>Part time (FTE)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£24,005</p></td><td><p>£22,195</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2014 Average FTE Salary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full time</p></td><td><p>Part time (FTE)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£23,663</p></td><td><p>£21,882</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2013 Average FTE Salary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full time</p></td><td><p>Part time (FTE)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£23,383</p></td><td><p>£21,680</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2012 Average FTE Salary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full time</p></td><td><p>Part time (FTE)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£22,935</p></td><td><p>£21,513</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2011 Average FTE Salary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full time</p></td><td><p>Part time (FTE)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£22,830</p></td><td><p>£21,393</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The main factor influencing the DWP gender and working pattern pay gap is the difference in distribution of staff within each of these groups across the grades. DWP continues to regularly review ways to address the pay gap.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-26T14:19:46.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452541/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452541/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of his Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452542","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-22","<p>DWP is currently considering the report from the National Federations of ALMOs and the Minister of State for Welfare Reform will be meeting to discuss their findings in due course.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-22T17:11:36.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452542/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452542/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Universal Credit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment for his policies of the findings of the National Federation of ALMOs Welfare reform survey relating to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","27076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452543","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-22","<p>For fatalities in construction (Standard Industrial Classification, section F) reported to HSE between 2006/07 and 2014/15, the average time between the date of the incident and the date of the first hearing where a conviction is recorded is 1208 days. The time between the incident and conviction dates by yearly time bands is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date of Conviction</p></td><td><p>Average number of days between incident date and conviction date</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/2007</p></td><td><p>985</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/2008</p></td><td><p>1234</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/2009</p></td><td><p>1153</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/2010</p></td><td><p>1214</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/2011</p></td><td><p>1251</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/2012</p></td><td><p>1251</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>1336</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>1185</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>1267</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Within the overall time frame from fatal incident to conviction a number of discrete stages may be involved and these are performed by different agencies largely out of HSE’s control:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>The police assume primacy initially and retain it until negligent homicide offences have been identified or eliminated.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>Where negligent homicide is suspected, the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) will consider a file submitted to them by the Police.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>HSE works closely with the police and CPS throughout this phase in accordance with the Work Related Deaths Protocol (WRDP) to which the Police, CPS, HSE and other regulators are signatories.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>Before HSE brings a prosecution it is normal to await the outcome of an inquest held by HM Coroner.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>If a defendant has been charged it can take some time for the case to come to trial particularly where if　it is defended and heard in the Crown Court.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Recognising the importance to victims of ensuring all stages of the process are concluded as quickly as possible, the WRDP National Liaison Committee recently agreed that any decision to prosecute should be made within 3 years of the date of death other than in exceptional circumstances – currently approximately 85% of investigations are completed within this timescale.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For its part HSE has an internal target of completing 95% of fatal accident investigations within 12 months of assuming primacy – attainment is now at 70% and the trend is improving.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-22T14:35:55.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452543/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452543/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-11","Construction: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time taken was between a fatal accident in construction and a conviction on the latest date for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","27162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453442","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>Complaints made against the police must be responded to in a way that builds public confidence, and allows lessons to be learned.</p><p>The Policing and Crime Bill will reform the complaints system so that the handling of police complaints is customer focused and that cases are dealt with quickly and effectively, not just for the benefits of the public, but also for officers who have done nothing wrong.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-22T17:28:00.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453442/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453442/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to reform the police complaints process.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","903680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453443","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The average processing time for disclosure applications is 15.3 days and 94.3% of applications are issued within 8 weeks, as of December 2015. Some Enhanced Certificate applications are referred to relevant police forces. DBS is working closely with the small number of forces whose performance does not meet turnaround targets.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-22T17:25:27.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453443/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453443/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the timeliness of the processing of Disclosure and Barring Service checks.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","903676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453444","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Government is committed to supporting the police and fire services to work more closely together. The Policing and Crime Bill includes a duty to collaborate and enables Police and Crime Commissioners to make the case to take on responsibility for fire and rescue locally, extending the benefits of directly elected, accountable leadership and driving collaboration.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-22T17:27:23.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453444/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453444/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Emergency Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the Government's policy is on steps to increase cooperation between police forces and fire services.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","903677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453445","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>We have ensured the police have the necessary powers and resources to tackle the terrorist threat, including in London, where the Metropolitan Police play a leading role in tackling terrorism across the country.</p><p>Counter-Terrorism Policing spending will be protected over the next Spending Review period. Indeed, for 2016/17 it will be increased in real terms to £670 million for England and Wales. An additional £34 million will also be provided to enable a national uplift in armed policing capability and capacity to respond more quickly and effectively to a firearms attack.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-02-23T14:05:49.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453445/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453445/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453445/answer/previousversion/46458","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Terrorism: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to support the Metropolitan Police in tackling terrorism in London.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","903681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453446","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<table><tbody><tr><td><p>The Home Secretary has regular meetings with policing partners on a range of issues, including police funding. The Government published the Final Police Grant Report for 2016/17 on 4 February following the usual public consultation. The Final Police Grant Report was approved by the House on 10 February. This represents a good settlement for policing.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-22T17:28:57.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453446/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453446/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-11","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with the police on the police grant settlement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","903683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453729","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), has been clear that the four priorities of our renegotiations are: economic governance; competitiveness; sovereignty; and benefits to EU migrants.</p><p>The EU budget financing system was agreed in 2013, when we secured an historic real-terms cut and protected the rebate. Parliament ratified that deal last year.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-23T15:38:44.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453729/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453729/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps have been taken during the Government's negotiations on the UK's membership of the EU to restore the UK's rebate to its full previous value.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","903716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453916","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","As The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) made clear in his statement to the House yesterday, the renegotiation deal delivers on the Government’s commitment to fix the problems with the EU that have frustrated people in the UK. It is legally binding, irreversible and delivers for the UK. The deal gives the UK the best of both worlds: in to the parts of Europe that work for us and out of those parts which don’t.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-02-23T16:40:34.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453916/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453916/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on the options circulated by the President of the European Council on the UK's relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","903715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453917","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>In 2013 we established high level prosperity partnerships with Angola, Cote d’Ivoire, Ghana, Mozambique and Tanzania. They form the context within which the UK seeks to increase mutual prosperity and generate jobs.</p><p>The recent appointment of The Rt Hon Baroness Northover as trade envoy for Angola, my Honourable Friend, the Member for Windsor, as trade envoy for Ghana and my Honourable Friend, the Member for Newbury, as trade envoy for Mozambique will further enhance these partnerships.</p><p>Our commitment to these agreements is illustrated by regular high-level visits, totalling 14 in the last three years.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-02-23T15:46:08.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453917/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453917/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Africa: Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent progress has been made on the High Level Prosperity Partnership in Africa.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","903717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453918","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Le Touquet Treaty is crucial to maintaining the UK’s border security. We meet regularly with our French Counterparts to discuss border security issues and look forward to further cementing our close cooperation at the upcoming UK-France summit on 3 March.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-23T15:39:29.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453918/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453918/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","France: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his French counterpart on the Treaty of Le Touquet; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","903706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453919","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>We have been clear that we want to see US presence continue. However, the Government has not yet held discussions with the US about continuing the agreement relating to Diego Garcia.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-02-23T15:43:53.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453919/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453919/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Diego Garcia: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the lease extension of the military base on Diego Garcia.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","903709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453920","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The ‘Registry of Attacks on Holy Sites in the Holy Land’ has listed 22 cases of vandalism and arson on Christian places of worship in Israel and the West Bank since February 2013, most recently vandalism against the Dormition Abbey compound on 17 January. We condemn all such attacks.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-23T14:55:04.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453920/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453920/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Israel: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of attacks on Christian places of worship in Israel in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","903711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453921","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The UK is committed to strengthening its engagement with the Commonwealth. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) led a strong delegation to the Commonwealth summit in November, where the Minister of State for Trade and Investment, my noble Friend, the right hon. Lord Maude and I promoted trade opportunities within the Commonwealth.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-23T16:15:53.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453921/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453921/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to promote trade and diplomatic connections between the UK and other Commonwealth countries.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","903718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453922","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>As The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) made clear in his statement to the House yesterday, the renegotiation deal delivers on the Government’s commitment to fix the problems with the EU that have frustrated people in the UK. It is legally binding, irreversible and delivers for the UK. The deal gives the UK the best of both worlds: in to the parts of Europe that work for us and out of those parts which don’t.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-02-23T16:28:29.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453922/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453922/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the outcome of discussions at the February 2016 European Council on the UK's relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","903714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453923","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>As, respectively, the world’s oldest and largest democracies, the United Kingdom and India have a strong friendship, which Prime Minister Modi’s visit has enhanced. We continue to work together to strengthen our defence and security partnership and expand trade and investment.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-02-23T16:25:15.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453923/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453923/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","India: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the strength of diplomatic and economic relations between India and the UK.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","903712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453924","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Government is committed to the success of the nuclear deal and we welcome the steps taken by Iran to comply - including decommissioning centrifuges and removing the core from Arak and exporting 90+% of its stock of enriched uranium - leading to Implementation Day on 16 January. We fully support expanding our trade relationship with Iran and are encouraging businesses to take advantage of the new opportunities that are available. Foreign Minister Zarif’s recent visit to London marked a significant step in our relationship with Iran.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-02-23T16:22:55.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453924/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453924/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on the implementation of the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action with Iran.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","903710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453925","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>We continue to encourage the Government of Bahrain to meet its human rights obligations and to honour all conventions to which it is a party. We welcome the progress made by Bahrain on their reform programme, particularly with organisations that provide independent oversight of police behaviour and standards in detention.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-23T15:48:02.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453925/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453925/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-11","Bahrain: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights situation in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","903713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454549","Wales Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>Wales Office Ministers have regular discussions with Welsh Ministers on a range of issues including how financial accountability can be strengthened by devolving tax raising powers. The Welsh Government will only become truly accountable when it takes responsibility for raising through taxation the money that it spends.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-02-24T15:57:29.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454549/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454549/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-02-11","Welsh Government: Accountability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with Ministers of the Welsh Government on strengthening financial accountability in government.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","903630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454550","Wales Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>My thoughts are with the workers and communities affected by the perfect storm currently facing the UK steel industry. We are doing everything we can to put the industry onto a sustainable footing and provide a level playing field.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this month, my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills and I visited Tata at Port Talbot to meet with management and the unions, as part of our continued engagement with the industry.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2016-02-24T15:55:38.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454550/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454550/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-02-11","Iron and Steel: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the future of the steel industry in Wales.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","903629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451842","Attorney General","false","2016-02-25","<p>By longstanding convention, the fact that the Law Officers have advised, or have not advised, and the content of their advice is not disclosed outside government.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-02-25T12:45:45.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451842/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451842/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-10","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the implications of the judgment of the European Court of Justice in the case of Costa v ENEL in July 1964 for the Government's policy on the relative relationship between EU and UK law.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","26879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451843","Attorney General","false","2016-02-29","<p>Criminal cases in Northern Ireland are the responsibility of the Public Prosecution Service for Northern Ireland. Its decisions are independently made and it reports to the devolved authorities.</p><p>In relation to offences involving attacks against armed forces in England and Wales, all cases referred to the CPS are reviewed in accordance with the Code for Crown Prosecutors by specialist prosecutors within the CPS Special Crime and Counter Terrorism Division. There is no specific policy in respect of prosecutions of this type and they will be dealt with in the usual way.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-29T11:21:49.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451843/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451843/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-10","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the CPS's policy is on seeking prosecutions of former members of paramilitary and terrorist organisations in Northern Ireland for attacks made against members of the armed forces during the Troubles; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","26902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451844","Attorney General","false","2016-02-24","<p>The information requested is contained in the attached tables.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-24T15:45:22.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451844/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451844/answer","Tables pay Law Officers Departments.docx","Tables pay Law Officers Departments.docx","Pay tables","Pay tables","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451844/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-10","Attorney General: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of the Law Officers' Departments were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","26972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451845","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Average earnings are published by the Office for National Statistics, for all departments on an annual basis. The latest publication date was 8 October 2015. Breaking these figures down to an hourly basis could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Detailed breakdowns of mean and median salaries for female, male, full time and part time staff are contained in the Civil Service Statistics Statistical Bulletin Tables available here:</p><p>2011: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-229310" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-229310</a></p><p>2012: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-279335" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-279335</a></p><p>2013: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-319802" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-319802</a></p><p>2014: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-375368" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-375368</a></p><p>2015: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-414427" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-414427</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-26T11:22:34.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451845/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451845/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the average hourly earnings of (a) female, (b) male, (c) full-time and (d) part-time employees of his Department were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","26971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451846","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Post Office Limited runs and manages its directly managed Crown post offices. Arrangements for employees of these offices and changes to the Crown network are the operational responsibility of the Post Office.</p><p>I have therefore asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to you on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","26943 ; 26944 ; 26946","2016-02-26T12:24:16.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451846/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451846/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the cost was to the public purse of settlement agreements for staff from  Crown Post Offices which were franchised in 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","26945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451847","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The allocation for the UK Space Agency for 2015/16 is £370.5 million with £302 million to be invested through the European Space Agency, £65 million to be invested on international programmes and £3.5 million on administration. In addition, £37 million was invested on space with the Met Office. Future allocations up to the end of the Parliament will be published in due course alongside the wider allocations of the science and research budget.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-22T17:23:19.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451847/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451847/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Space Technology: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the total public expenditure on the UK space industry over the course of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","26968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451848","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Post Office Limited runs and manages its directly managed Crown post offices. Arrangements for employees of these offices and changes to the Crown network are the operational responsibility of the Post Office.</p><p>I have therefore asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to you on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","26943 ; 26944 ; 26945","2016-02-26T12:24:17.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451848/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451848/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Offices: Lancaster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the cost to the public purse has been of the refurbishment of Crown Post Offices in Lancaster since January 2010.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","26946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451849","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>Post Office Limited runs and manages its directly managed Crown post offices. Employees of these offices are employees of Post Office Limited. Changes to the Crown network are the operational responsibility of the Post Office, and HM Government has not undertaken any analysis of the changes to the benefit and tax credit demand from these changes.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-22T17:29:59.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451849/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451849/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on benefit and tax credit demand from workers at franchises of former post offices; and what estimate his Department has made of the potential cost of that demand to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","26970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451850","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The levels of premium pay in Scotland will be a result of a range of factors and businesses will ultimately be constrained by the need to hire the quality and quantity of shop workers they need in local markets.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-03T17:19:05.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451850/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451850/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of Sunday trading devolution on the premium pay of shop workers in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","26897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451851","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government’s estimates of the economic impact will be independently scrutinised by the Regulatory Policy Committee and their assessment will be published in due course.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:39:46.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451851/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451851/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Regulatory Policy Committee has made of the devolution of Sunday trading rules.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","26898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451852","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department does not hold full data from this consultation broken down by specific question as a large portion of respondents chose to respond in their own words rather than addressing the consultation questions directly, and/or did not indicate the type of organisation they represented.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T10:17:01.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451852/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451852/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many (a) business representative bodies, (b) central government bodies, (c) local authorities, (d) trade union or staff associations, (e) charity and social enterprises, (f) large businesses, (g) medium-sized businesses, (h) small businesses, (i) micro businesses, (j) convenience stores, (k) shop workers, (l) legal representatives, (m) religious organisations, (n) individuals and (o) other bodies responded to the consultation on Sunday trading devolution; how many responses of each category (i) supported and (ii) opposed devolution.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","26899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451853","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-22","<p>We have not made an assessment of the potential effect of a British exit from the EU on the international legal enforceability of protected UK food names.</p><p>Separately, the Government is taking steps to achieve a significant increase in the number of UK food products covered by the EU’s protected food names scheme. We continue to exert pressure on the European Commission to secure wider international recognition of these products, as well as our wines and spirits drinks that are protected by Geographical Indications, in the context of EU bilateral trade negotiations.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-22T17:45:31.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451853/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451853/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-10","Food: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of a British exit from the EU on the international legal enforceability of protected UK food names.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","26883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451854","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>Further to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member in November to UIN 17111, I can confirm that a consultation will be launched shortly.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-22T15:37:51.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451854/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451854/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government plans to start the consultation on introducing legislative change to require transparency of the beneficial ownership of all UK properties.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","26884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451855","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Post Office Limited runs and manages its directly managed Crown post offices. Arrangements for employees of these offices and changes to the Crown network are the operational responsibility of the Post Office.</p><p> </p><p>I have therefore asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-22T17:17:45.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451855/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451855/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Offices: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Post Office has spent refurbishing the premises of the Crown Post Office in Walworth Road since January 2010.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","26885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451856","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>In 2006 Indepen were commissioned by the Department for Trade and Industry to evaluate the economic costs and benefits of extending Sunday Trading hours, a copy of the report can be found on the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p>Neither my Department nor another Department has commissioned independent research since then on the economic effects of extending Sunday trading hours, although, we are aware of recent independent research from the London School of Economics that found evidence of positive impacts in retail on employment and expenditure.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-22T17:36:46.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451856/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451856/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether (a) his Department and (b) another department has commissioned independent research on the economic effects of extending Sunday trading hours.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","26886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451857","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Provision of the post office network is the operational responsibility of the Post Office.</p><p>I have therefore asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to you on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-26T12:39:06.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451857/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451857/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many (a) local and (b) main post offices were open at the end of (i) April 2015 and (ii) January 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","26942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451858","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Ministers have acknowledged that the £1 trillion target is a stretch; however, the Government has a clear strategy for increasing both the value of UK exports and the number of British exporters.</p><p> </p><p>This is set out in the Government’s <a href="http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/business-innovation-and-skills-committee/exports-and-the-role-of-ukti/written/27001.html" target="_blank">evidence</a> to the BIS Select Committee inquiry into Exports and the Role of UK Trade &amp; Investment. Progress in delivering against the target will be reported through the ONS.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-26T14:09:38.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451858/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451858/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the ability of the Government to reach the target set in 2012 of doubling exports to £1 trillion per annum by 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","26930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451859","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Post Office Limited runs and manages its directly managed Crown post offices. Arrangements for employees of these offices and changes to the Crown network are the operational responsibility of the Post Office.</p><p>I have therefore asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to you on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","26944 ; 26945 ; 26946","2016-02-26T12:24:16.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451859/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451859/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff from Crown Post Offices that were franchised in 2014 and 2015 (a) transferred to employment with a franchise partner and (b) reached settlement agreements with the Post Office to leave its employment.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","26943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451860","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government is working with the energy industry to maximise economic benefits from new electricity generation projects and is providing support to enhance the competitiveness of the supply chain, including improving the skills and employability of the construction workers in the industry.</p><p> </p><p>In addition Cumbria Local Enterprise Partnership has identified nuclear and energy excellence as a key priority contributing significant growth opportunities for the Cumbria economy. The Local Enterprise Partnership has strong ambitions to drive growth across the Cumbria area by improving the delivery of skills, infrastructure, environmental sustainability and business support.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","26932","2016-02-26T14:13:35.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451860/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451860/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Job Creation: Sellafield and Solway Firth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to ensure that jobs created by the (a) new nuclear project at Moorside and (b) the Solway Firth Tidal Lagoon project are available to local people.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","26931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451861","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Post Office Limited runs and manages its directly managed Crown post offices. Arrangements for employees of these offices and changes to the Crown network are the operational responsibility of the Post Office.</p><p>I have therefore asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to you on this matter. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","26943 ; 26945 ; 26946","2016-02-26T12:24:16.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451861/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451861/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Post Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the cost was to the public purse of indemnification of franchise partners to meet the costs for staff from Crown Post Offices who transferred into their employment in 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","26944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451862","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government is working with the energy industry to maximise economic benefits from new electricity generation projects and is providing support to enhance the competitiveness of the supply chain, including improving the skills and employability of the construction workers in the industry.</p><p> </p><p>In addition Cumbria Local Enterprise Partnership has identified nuclear and energy excellence as a key priority contributing significant growth opportunities for the Cumbria economy. The Local Enterprise Partnership has strong ambitions to drive growth across the Cumbria area by improving the delivery of skills, infrastructure, environmental sustainability and business support.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","26931","2016-02-26T14:13:35.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451862/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451862/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Skilled Workers: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he has taken to ensure that young people in West Cumbria are equipped with the skills they need to access newly-created jobs in the nuclear and renewable energy sectors.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","26932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451863","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The US and Russia are both treated as market economies in anti-dumping investigations by the European Commission. This means that, with some exceptions, dumping is calculated on the basis of prices prevailing in the US and Russian domestic market. The exceptions are set out in Council Regulation (EC) No 1225/2009 (the EU’s basic anti-dumping Regulation) and the World Trade Organisation Agreement on Implementation of Article VI of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 1994 (the “AD agreement”).</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-26T14:11:03.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451863/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451863/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Antidumping: Russia and USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24530, what methodology is used to calculate prices in connection with anti-dumping cases relating to the US and Russia.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","26753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451864","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>It is for industry to demonstrate <em>prima facie</em> evidence of dumping to the European Commission. We encourage industry to present this evidence to the Commission where there is evidence of dumping. Where evidence is sufficient to justify an investigation the Commission will do so and present any proposals for imposing duties to Member States. Trade defence is an EU competence and for the Commission to investigate.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-26T14:18:20.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451864/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451864/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Ceramics: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will make an assessment of whether prices of imported ceramic goods from China reflect the domestic costs of production.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","26754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451865","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-22","<p>HM Treasury does not hold information on the number of people who accumulate credit card debt.</p><p> </p><p>Publically available information on consumer credit, including credit card debt, is available up to Q4 2015 from the Bank of England. The most recent statistical release can be accessed at: <a href="http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/Pages/bankstats/2015/dec.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/Pages/bankstats/2015/dec.aspx</a></p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-22T17:21:01.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451865/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-10","Credit Cards: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people who accumulate credit card debt after the Christmas period.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","26765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451866","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold full data from this consultation broken down by specific question as a large portion of respondents chose to respond in their own words rather than addressing the consultation questions directly, and/or did not indicate the type of organisation they represented.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-26T14:47:37.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451866/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451866/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many responses his Department received from (a) convenience stores, (b) shop workers and (c) faith groups to the consultation on Sunday trading devolution.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","26782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451867","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>If staff are on a detached duty or overseas postings they can claim for certain travel expenses. Out of 2514 employees in BIS HQ, fewer than 20 employees are paid reasonable extra travel costs. These are paid for a limited period.</p><p> </p><p>There are no BIS policies that allow the payments of car allowances or subsidised health insurance to employees. However BIS has a legal obligation to honour contractual arrangements when staff join through a TUPE transfer including car allowances and subsidised health cover. Due to TUPE transfers, there are fewer than 20 employees paid car allowances or subsidised health cover. These benefits would not be renewed for new employees.</p><p> </p><p>As the number of payments are so low, exact numbers have not been provided to ensure that individual employees are not identifiable.</p><p> </p><p>The requested information is not held by BIS in respect of non-Departmental Public Bodies.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-26T14:42:03.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451867/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451867/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Fringe Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff in his Department and non-departmental public bodies receive (a) home to work travel allowance, (b) a car allowance and (c) subsidised health insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","26810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451868","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>The investment protection provisions of trade and investment agreements such as the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) and the EU-US Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) will typically apply to the acts of local authorities but claims under the investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) mechanisms of those agreements may only be brought against the UK or the EU.</p><p>The question of investment protection and ISDS provisions in TTIP is still under negotiation. The Government wants any such provisions to reflect the right of governments to act in the public interest and deter investors from making unnecessary and speculative claims.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-26T11:58:56.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451868/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451868/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Trade Agreements: North America","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the investor-state dispute settlement mechanisms in the (a) Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) agreement and (b) EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) apply to local authorities in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","26772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451870","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department does not hold full data from this consultation broken down by specific question as a large portion of respondents chose to respond in their own words rather than addressing the consultation questions directly, and/or did not indicate the type of organisation they represented.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","26803","2016-02-29T10:10:02.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451870/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451870/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many (a) business representative bodies, (b) central government bodies, (c) charity and social enterprises, (d) individuals, (e) large businesses, (f) legal representatives, (g) local authorities, (h) medium-sized businesses, (i) micro businesses, (j) religious organisations, (k) small businesses, (l) trade union or staff associations and (m) other bodies responded to the consultation on Sunday trading devolution; how many of each category (i) supported and (ii) opposed devolution; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","26805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451871","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Government has protected the science budget in real terms to the end of the Parliament. Our intention is to formally allocate budgets to individual funding bodies in the coming weeks. The Government recognises the significant contribution made by charitable funders of research, which the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE), has reflected through the charity support element of Quality Related research funding. Decisions by HEFCE on any funding beyond 2015-16 will be taken once they have received their annual Grant Letter which, sets out their funding allocations.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-26T11:46:41.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451871/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451871/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Charity Research Support Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will maintain the level of funding of the Charity Research Support Fund in real terms over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451872","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department does not hold full data from this consultation broken down by specific question as a large portion of respondents chose to respond in their own words rather than addressing the consultation questions directly, and/or did not indicate the type of organisation they represented.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","26805","2016-02-29T10:10:02.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451872/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451872/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of responses to the Sunday trading consultation supported the devolution of Sunday trading hours.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","26803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451873","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-20","<p>In view of the will of the House of Commons, we are no longer proposing to give local authorities the ability to extend the Sunday trading hours of large shops.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-20T08:16:29.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451873/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451873/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of Sunday trading devolution on the premium pay of shopworkers.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","26780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451874","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-24","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government’s estimates of the economic impact will be independently scrutinised by the Regulatory Policy Committee and their assessment will be published in due course.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-24T16:21:18.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451874/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451874/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Regulatory Policy Committee has made of the devolution of Sunday trading rules.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","26781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451875","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p>Government will produce an evaluation of the area review programme and its potential to impact on groups protected by the Equality Act 2010. The reviews do not however, mandate action, and colleges are independent corporations, so it will be for each college’s governing body to assess the potential impact on groups protected by the Act, as part of its decision to accept or reject any recommendation requiring a change to their provision.</p><p>Each area review steering group will consider relevant data relating to current courses delivered within their area, assess the relevance of these courses to local learner and employer needs and determine how current and future demand can be best met through the recommendations of the area review.</p><p>Individual area reviews are expected to take about four months, the timescale being dependent on the number of colleges and complexity of the local issues involved in each area. The overall review process has been divided into five waves of area reviews and is scheduled to be completed by March 2017</p><p>We expect the costs of completing an area review to be met within existing budgets, with minimal additional costs to the colleges, local authorities or LEPs involved. The Departments and their agencies will undertake this work with no additional staffing. Additional costs will be minimal.</p><p>The costs arising from the recommendations of each review will be explored as part of the process. We expect the colleges, alongside local authorities and LEPs with devolved skills budgets, to consider how these costs can be met locally. Where there are costs that cannot be met, but which are essential to the successful implementation of the review, we have announced a facility for transitional funding to support this. We will provide more detail in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","26834 ; 26838 ; 26839","2016-02-26T13:33:10.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451875/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451875/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he plans that his Department's further education area reviews will incorporate equality impact assessments.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","26840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451876","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-23","<p>This Government is absolutely clear that anyone entitled to be paid the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and, from April 2016, the National Living Wage, should receive it. The Department for Business, Innovations and Skills (BIS) are responsible for the policy on NMW compliance and enforcement, and HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) enforces the NMW Act on BIS’s behalf.</p><p>HMRC responds to all worker complaints. Where NMW arrears are identified, HMRC ensures the employer corrects the position for all their workers and pays any outstanding arrears. HMRC carries out follow-up checks to ensure arrears have been paid. If subsequent issues are found HMRC will investigate and, if arrears are identified, take further action.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-23T15:37:28.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451876/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451876/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to his Department's press release of 5 February 2016, New National Minimum Wage offenders named and shamed, whether HM Revenue and Customs follows up successful investigations into companies found not to have complied with national minimum wage legislation with additional investigations into whether other employees of the same company were also not in receipt of the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","26841"
